<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Ackerman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>, 75, the powerful political activist whose support was courted by candidates ranging from condominum board members to a president, died Monday of cancer. Ms. <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> political activism included volunteer work for the campaigns of the late Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and accelerated when she moved to a waterfront <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> condominium in 1969. Ms. <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> successfully roused retirees from political apathy and mobilized them into powerful voting blocs. Famed for turnouts ranging past 90 percent, they were dubbed `` condo commandos.'' Her political friends included President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, fellow Democrats <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, and nearly every well-known Democratic politician in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Boyd</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON>, who fought off leftists to lead the powerful British union of engineering workers, died Sunday. He was 71. A cause of death was not available. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> started his career as an engineering worker but began work as a trade union organizer in 1946. He stepped up to the presidency of the <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> in 1964. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> spent years fighting communists and left-wing elements for control of the 1.5 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Amalgamated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>. From 1975 to 1982, he served as general secretary of the union, which is one of the largest in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. From 1967 to 1975, <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> sat on the general council of the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the national organization of unions. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> was a director of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> from 1981-86. A chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1967, he was knighted in 1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Malley</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST SENECA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Malley </PERSON> a deputy managing editor at The Buffalo News was killed Sunday after his car spun out of control. He was 49. <PERSON> Malley </PERSON> joined The News as a copy editor in 1966 and was promoted to assistant news editor in 1969 and then Sunday magazine editor in 1977. He was named assistant managing editor in 1980 and deputy managing editor in 1987.
