<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Illinois Death Penalty Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 7 grafs after 6th graf, `Judge threw ...,' to UPDATE
with reaction; picks up 7th graf, `Baker's ruling ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Monday struck down <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>' death penalty law, raising doubts about the fate of 121 prisoners on the state's Death Row, including serial killer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacy </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> ruled that the 1977 law gives prosecutors too much discretion in deciding when to seek the death penalty, violating <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> directives that capital punishment not be imposed in an `` arbitrary and capricious'' manner. If sustained on appeal, the decision would invalidate the sentences of the 121 men currently facing the death penalty in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. They include <PERSON> Gacy </PERSON>, convicted in 1980 of killing 33 young men and boys in the worst multiple-killing case in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. Prosecutors said they were confident the ruling would be overturned by the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. No one has been executed under the state's death penalty law, which was upheld by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1979. Judges threw out three earlier death sentences that emerged through the appeals process in federal court, but Monday's ruling was the first to address the constitutionality of the law. `` I think we knew that in some case, a -LRB- federal -RRB- judge would rule specifically on the statute,'' said <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottfried </PERSON>, head of the state appellate defender's office, which handles appeals for death row inmates. `` We did n't know which case it would be.'' First Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ficaro </PERSON> defended the death penalty law. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has dealt with that issue over 60 times,'' <PERSON> Ficaro </PERSON> said. `` We believe the statute is constitutional.'' <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, director of the state's <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> chapter, said, `` We're delighted with any decision that finds any death penalty law unconstitutional. `` We think they're all unconstitutional,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think there's any way to write a death penalty law that's constitutional. Legal experts agreed a ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> appelate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> is virtually a certainty. Should the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decline to review that ruling, it would in effect become the last word on the law's validity. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s ruling came in the case of a double killer, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Silagy </PERSON>, who demanded the death penalty after being convicted in 1980 of a double killing in <LOCATION> Vermilion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Silagy </PERSON>, who has been on death row since August 1980, had his sentence appealed twice to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and once to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, but was unsuccessful until his case reached <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> in one of the last stages of the death-penalty appeals process. The state's capital punishment law allows a trial court to consider a death sentence in certain circumstances, such as a multiple killing, when requested by the prosecution. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the law in 4-3 ruling in 1979. Dissenting Justice <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, whose opinion was cited by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, wrote: `` Our statute contains no directions or guidelines to minimize the risk of wholly arbitrary and capricious action by the prosecutor in either requesting or in not requesting a -LRB- death sentence -RRB- hearing.''
