<HEAD>West Germans Step Up Campaign For Missile Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 3rd pvs `Both the...' to UPDATE with
newspaper report of emerging compromise; pickup 4th graf pvs `In Washington...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government began a new effort Monday to rally <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies behind its proposal for superpower talks on reducing short-range nuclear weapons, which has caused a dispute with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> was quoted as saying <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s argument must have `` special weight'' because it is the alliance's front line, and a war with such battlefield-range weapons would be fought on its territory. Both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> say the negotiations proposed by Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> might endanger Western security. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that the elements of a compromise have begun to emerge with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal submitted to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. Quoting unidentified diplomats from several nations, the newspaper said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> proposed Wednesday that the alliance decide to upgrade the weapons and then announce unilateral reductions. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> would then challenge the Soviets to make cuts to the lower levels. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Monday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remains committed to a mixture of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> conventional and nuclear forces, called flexible response, as a deterrent to attack. `` The West German position demonstrates the special strength that <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` Our allies can debate quite vigorously these issues, yet maintain the basic strength of our unity. `` Our position remains that keeping the peace requires a strong <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance and a policy of flexible response.'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s remarks were the first official West German comment since a meeting Sunday in which Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> tried, but failed, to change <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s mind on the issue. In pursuit of support for the West German position, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> plans to visit <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Tuesday and <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> will go to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> has said it agrees with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> that negotiations on the short-range weapons should begin, but <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> has not made its position clear. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> claims the support of seven of the 16 <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orgnization </ORGANIZATION> members. In an interview with the <PERSON> Frankfurter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rundschau </PERSON>, <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> was quoted as saying: `` This is not a new demand that has only now been made by us and other alliance partners. This concerns putting into effect an intention which has already been stated in two alliance decisions.'' His ministry made copies of the interview available to other news organizations before publication in the paper's Tuesday editions. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> has noted previously the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> decision at summits in 1987 and 1988 that negotiations on short-range nuclear weapons should be held at some point. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> say this is not the time. `` Naturally the German view must have a special weight because the Lance rockets are on our soil and because our army represents the largest conventional contribution -LRB- in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB- to the common Western security,'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s army has about 500,000 soldiers. Most of the alliance's short-range Lance rockets are on its territory and would be used there in a war. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> say <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> should not pass up opportunities to negotiate in important areas of disarmament, and they insist the time is right for taking up the battlefield-range weapons. The chancellor has said he wants the talks to begin `` soon,'' but has not proposed a timetable. A West German government official said privately Monday the chancellor was `` optimistic'' about a compromise. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials say starting negotiations now could lead to elimination of the short-range weapons and increase the threat from the Soviet bloc's superior conventional forces. After the meeting with Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> on Sunday, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said he does not favor pulling the Lance missiles out of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> `` under the present circumstances.'' Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON>, the American who commands <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, was quoted as saying he did not believe there was disagreement on strategy within the alliance. In an interview for publication Tuesday, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Die </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welt </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> as saying: `` Recent statements make it very clear that there are no differences in the grand strategy. The importance of nuclear deterrence is recognized.''
