<HEAD>Political Aide's Suicide Spotlights Japan's Money Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the prime minister's political secretary committed suicide, many saw him as a victim of the money politics entwined with Japanese culture and tradition. Beside such Western-style institutions as a parliament and free elections, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has customs that demand exchanges of gifts and favors and lingering ideals of absolute loyalty. Japanese politicians spend campaign money in a very personal manner. Voters expect their representatives not only to bring pork-barrel projects to the district, but to help their children find jobs in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, attend weddings and send donations to funerals. Political secretaries spend much of their time going to family ceremonies and delivering obligatory gifts. Results of a survey published in the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> said a legislator or his representative attends, on average, 26.5 funerals a month. <PERSON> Ihei </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>, for three decades Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s closest aide, may have killed himself Wednesday because more than $ 1 million in donations and loans he received from the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> helped bring down his boss, who had announced the day before he would resign `` The tragic case of <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>'s suicide pathetically calls for a drastic reform of the money-oriented structure of politics,'' the daily <ORGANIZATION> Yomiuri </ORGANIZATION> said in an editorial. <PERSON> Asahi </PERSON> said political aides `` function as ` cloaks' that cover up foul play.'' Of 13 politicians linked to the Recruit scandal, it noted, six took donations in aides' names rather than their own. Political secretaries, who would be called legislative assistants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, carry a burden imposed by the money-driven election system. Most spend hardly any time drafting legislation, a job generally handled by bureaucrats. <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>'s main task as secretary to a top leader was `` to raise money from big business and distribute it to legislators,'' said <PERSON> Kotaru </PERSON> <PERSON> Nogami </PERSON>, chief political editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Secretaries of legislators, in turn, pass some of the largesse on to their districts. `` Basically, a secretary does everything and anything he is told to do and he has to carry out any order to perfection, even though specific guidelines are not given,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Redl </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, a political secretary to a legislator of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. When he began working in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Redl </PERSON> said, he was surprised to see aides in funny costumes dancing to entertain constituents at a local festival. He said he was exhausted by the dawn-to-2-a.m. schedule of courtesy calls and parties with supporters in the Hokkaido district of his legislator, <PERSON> Shizuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>. `` I talked to another secretary who had to do this all the time,'' the American said. `` He told me, ` It's like the old days. You have to be ready to die for your shogun.''' When <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON> killed himself, many people were reminded of the suicide in 1976 of former Prime Minister <PERSON> Kakuei </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanaka </PERSON>'s driver, who had carried payoff money in the <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> scandal. <PERSON> Tanaka </PERSON> eventually was convicted on a bribery charge. `` After the <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> scandal there was a lot of discussion of political reform, but it was never carried out,'' <PERSON> Nogami </PERSON> said. A partial reform limited donations, but the Recruit case revealed ways around it: buying many tickets to fund-raising parties and selling shares at bargain prices before offering them for public sale. Recruit was limited to contributing $ 115,000 a year to all politicians. In three years, however, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> alone got more than $ 1.5 million from the company in donations, stock-sale profits, loans and proceeds from ticket purchases. All of it went through <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>'s hands. Such huge sums of money are needed, in part, because taxes cover only a fraction of what it costs to run the parliament. `` The Recruit scandal was born of the system,'' said <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>, 47, the young American's boss. He is a member of the governing party's cmmittee on reform and wants more government funds so legislators will be less dependent on contributions In the tiny office the government provides, he told an interviewer: `` The budget from the government allows for only two aides. I have 15.'' His monthly travel allowance of $ 500 covers just a quarter of what he spends visiting his constituency. <PERSON> Sato </PERSON> depends on a patron, former Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>, for political funds, and in return backs <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> in intra-party maneuvers. Patrons like <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> or <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> lead <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> factions that operate almost as separate parties, particularly in raising money. Explaining how Japanese politicians spend campaign funds in their districts, <PERSON> Sato </PERSON> said: `` It's different from <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. A simple television ad wo n't get votes. It's a matter of obligation and human feelings.'' Americans might see the exchanges of favors and money as graft or vote-buying, but in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> they generally are considered social custom. Contributions by Recruit were at the top level of an interlocking system of gifts and obligations stretching down to ordinary citizens. Some Japanese say they do n't mind politicians collecting large amounts of money because they usually recirculate it rather than enriching themselves. Giving gift envelopes of cash at weddings, funerals and bon voyage parties, even between parents and children at the New Year, is a matter of etiquette in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. A parliamentary survey indicated young legislators spent an average of $ 274,000 a year on cash gifts for funerals, weddings, community festivals and local clubs. `` When a politician gives money at a funeral, it's not because he's a politician but because it's a matter of Japanese custom,'' <PERSON> Sato </PERSON> said. `` Now it may be necessary for us to distance ourselves from Japanese habits.'' Among reforms an advisory group suggested to <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> last week was prohibiting parliament members from giving money at weddings and funerals.
</TEXT>
