<HEAD>Riots Distance Jordan From Israeli Hopes</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The riots that shook the kingdom have turned <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s focus toward internal problems and made the country less of a factor in the Israel-Palestinian controversy over the future of the occupied territories. It has become increasingly clear that King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> was serious last year when he vowed never to negotiate on behalf of the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION>, saying it is a matter between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> themselves. The king was bowing to the obvious: The Palestinian uprising on the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> of the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which he ruled until 1967, showed he had little remaining loyalty there. It had shifted to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Even the idea of a confederation between <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state _ a proposal to make <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> independence palatable to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ seems only remotely possible these days. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> for months has said he will consider a confederation only after a Palestinian state is created, and only if Palestinians there and <LOCATION> Jordanians </LOCATION> in his country vote for it. Many old-line Jordanians, or East Bankers, oppose a confederation because it could give <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> a larger say in <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> affairs. Palestinians already make up half of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s 3 million people. Palestinians were almost nowhere to be seen in the four days of rioting that began on April 18 and rocked more than a dozen towns and villages in southern <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, the bedrock of support for <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>. The rioting, in which at least nine people were killed, was sparked by government-imposed price increases but contained a cry by East Bankers that <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> pay attention to their problems and give them a greater voice in running the country. Some have resented the prosperity and political prominence of <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION>, who were granted full citizenship when <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> merged with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in 1950. Some also hold a grudge from 1969 and 1970, when <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas began to set up a state within a state in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, often harassing East Bankers at guerrilla roadblocks. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s selection Thursday of Field Marshal <PERSON> Zeid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaker </PERSON>, the former army commander, as prime minister partly answered that plea. <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaker </PERSON>, a man of Bedouin stock, commands wide loyalty in the armed forces, which are still a favored occupation for Bedouin youth. He also was prominent in crushing the guerrilla movement in 1970. He replaces <PERSON> Zaid </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifai </PERSON>, whose Jordanian birth was not enough in the eyes of many <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> eyes to compensate for his father's Palestinian origins <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> will not renounce the Palestinians in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> itself. He has woven them into the fabric of his society, along with smaller immigrant groups such as Armenians and Circassians. But the king has demanded they act as Jordanians and his security forces watch closely for any expressions of domestic Palestinian nationalism. Israeli leaders still speak often of turning part of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> back to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> or putting it under the control of Jordanian security forces. But hard-line Israelis refuse to give up any of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> or consider any form of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> entity. They say there already is a <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. However, some of the resentments that led to the recent rioting demonstrate that <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> is not a Palestinian state. No amount of introspection will keep <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> from being an essential player in <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace maneuvering. It shares <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s longest border and is permanently threatened by a conflict that has twice swamped <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> with refugees. The king has vowed to maintain his support of the Palestinians in the occupied lands and has been an important moderating force on the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s negotiating demands. His abandonment of claims to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> helped push the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> to focus its attention on ending Israeli occupation there. And the Palestinian organization followed <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s longstanding appeal that it formally endorse <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. That led the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to open a dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> in December and turn its gaze away from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> as the answer to the 41-year conflict. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> is urging Israelis to do the same.
</TEXT>
