<HEAD>Tropical Oil Use Down in US Food Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The use of so-called tropical oils by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food manufacturers has fallen considerably in recent years, but the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says it wo n't make much difference economically. Imported products such as palm oil, palm kernel oil and coconut oil have been attacked vigorously by many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm and consumer interests because of their high levels of saturated fats and possible effects on health. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> used about 14.5 billion pounds of fats and oils in food products in the last year but that only 550 million pounds, or 4 percent, were tropical oils. Soybean oil accounted for more than 10 billion pounds; corn oil, 950 million pounds; and cottonseed oil, 800 million. Animal fats _ lard and tallow _ totaled about 1.1 billion pounds. Other sources of vegetable oil include sunflower seed and rapeseed. Major edible uses of fats and oils are salad and cooking oils; baking and frying fats; and margarine. Economists <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON> said that use of tropical oils in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may average about 1.84 billion pounds since 1985, but the portion used in food products is expected to average only about 650 million pounds a year, down from the record 1.6 billion pounds in the mid-1970s. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, after watching palm oil and other tropical oils nudge into the lucrative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, launched a campaign highlighting the health benefits of soybean oil's relatively low saturated fat content. <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON>, writing in the May issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine, said the soybean people were joined by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which began promoting the use of oils low in saturated fats. Tropical oil interests deny adverse health effects, and the <ORGANIZATION> Malaysian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has mounted an information campaign and has underwritten medical studies to support its case. But <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON> said saturated fats `` have been linked with high blood cholesterol levels and heart disease,'' citing last year's report by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> surgeon general recommending reduced intake of dietary fats, especially saturated fats. Several major food companies have eliminated tropical oils in all or most of their products, and others plan to follow. `` If edible use of tropical oils were cut 50 percent, the effect on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fats and oils markets would be marginal, because these oils are only a small portion of total use,'' the economists said in their report. `` Substitute oils would capture some of the small market share held by tropical oils.'' The report added: `` Prices also would be little affected. Those manufacturers using large quantities of relatively low-priced palm oil would experience the largest impact. Consumers would hardly be affected, because tropical oils account for only a small part of the price of finished food products.'' <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON> also said that a 50 percent reduction in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food use of tropical oils would have little effect on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports and world trade, and the effect on suppliers such as <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> would likewise be minor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A final order is expected to be issued soon by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> clearing the way for a watermelon checkoff plan to finance a national research and promotion program. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the next steps after the formal order is to hold meetings and solicit nominations for a 29-member board that will oversee the program. Those nominations are expected to be submitted by the end of July. After a board is selected, a proposed spending budget will be drawn up and submitted for review. The agency says it may be fall or later before everything is wrapped up. In any case, the watermelon assessments _ which are mandatory but can be refunded _ are expected to be ready for 1990 production. The assessments and the program were authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1985 farm law. A referendum was held in February in which approximately 52 percent of the growers and 56 percent of the handlers approved the plan. Agency officials said an estimated 7,000 watermelon producers and handlers would be covered by the checkoff program. The assessment, to be recommended by the board and then set by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, can be levied at rate of up to two cents per 100 pounds of watermelons sold by producers and two cents per 100 pounds for handlers. All producers of watermelons having five acres or more and first handlers are required to pay the assessment. A grower of five acres or more who also handles watermelons would have to pay both assessments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of cut flowers, potted plants, greenery and other commercially grown floriculture crops in 1988, a time of severe drought in much of the nation, dropped 2 percent to an estimated $ 2.24 billion, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. An annual survey of 28 crops showed that wholesale values of cut flowers increased 3 percent from 1987 to about $ 452 million, while the value of potted flowering plants declined 3 percent to $ 494 million. Sales of foliage, including hanging baskets and potted foliage, declined 7 percent to $ 477 million. The wholesale value of plants used for bedding and gardens declined 2 percent to $ 724 million last year, the report said.
