<HEAD>Student Council Tenatively Reverses Resolution Asking ROTC Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s undergraduate student council has reversed its decision to ask <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> back to the campus, declaring an earlier vote a violation of the undergraduate constitution. But the debate is not over. The university forced Reserve Officers' Training Corps programs from campus in 1969 by declaring the programs extracurricular activities without special privileges. The move followed a building takeover and student strike. Last week, the student council voted 41-24 to ask the administration to negotiate with the military and bring ROTC back. Sunday night, about 400 students attended the meeting where the council voted 43-39 against its week-old resolution. The resolution effectively said bringing <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> back was in violation of the student constitution because the program denies membership and, therefore, scholarships to homosexual students. About 150 activists wearing pink arm bands and T-shirts demonstrated outside before the meeting and chanted, `` 2-4-6-8, no to <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> _ gay or straight!'' During the debate, some students argued that barring <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> may deny economically disadvantaged students ROTC benefits. `` The issue is one of symbolism verses practicality,'' said <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, who supported bringing ROTC back. Others said fewer than 20 of the 150 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> students who take part in ROTC programs do so at nearby <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> and receive less money from <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> because their program was not on campus. `` Harvard has a need-blind admissions policy,'' said <PERSON> Deepak </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhargava </PERSON>, a ROTC opponent. `` If it's not living up to this policy, we should force it to do so.'' Although the council reversed itself Sunday, members next week will consider the measure that would approve <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> on campus if the military did not bar homosexuals.
