<HEAD>India Again Postpones Ballistic Missile Test-firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIPUR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> today postponed the test-firing of its first intermediate-range ballistic missile for a second time after a leak was discovered in the rocket's liquid fuel propellant, military sources said. A military official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said scientists detected the leak minutes before the scheduled launch time and attempts to repair it quickly were abandoned three hours later. On April 20, firing of the missile, named `` Agni'', was canceled after a last-minute hitch in the ignition system. The military official said senior defense officers and scientists had not yet decided when a third attempt would be made. The 7.5-ton missile has a range of 1,550 miles, Indian military experts say. It was to be boosted in the first stage by a solid propellant engine and in the second stage by a liquid fuel motor. A successful launch would make <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> the sixth nation in the world to demonstrate ballistic missile capability. The others are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Agni _ fire in the Hindi language _ was to have been launched from the Chandipur test range on the Bay of <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> about 750 miles southeast of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. The postponement was met by cheers and blowing of conch shells by many of the 12,000 villagers who were temporarily evacuated from their homes around the launch site. The villagers fear they will be permanently shifted from their homes if the missile launch is successful and the test range is used for more firings. <PERSON> Agni </PERSON> is the fourth missile <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has developed since the Integrated Guided Missile Development Program started in 1983. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has already test-fired three surface-to-surface and surface-to-air missiles with ranges from 20 to 155 miles. Defense experts say <PERSON> Agni </PERSON>'s one-ton payload enables it to carry a nuclear warhead, although <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> has said its demonstrated nuclear capability is for peaceful purposes such as generating power. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> exploded a nuclear device 15 years ago, and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> nuclear experts believe scientists can assemble an atomic weapon in one week. The test-firing of the Intermediate Range Ballistic Missile is intended to be only `` a technology demonstration of the country's capabilities,'' according to the government
