<HEAD>`Ghetto,' A Play by Joshua Sobol, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with comments from other critics; No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two months after 50,000 of the 70,000 Eastern European Jews living in the Vilna Ghetto of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during World War II were slaughtered, a theater company was started by some of the survivors. It was an extraordinary event _ the founding of an artistic community at the height of the Holocaust to keep alive the spirits as well as the lives of those still trapped by its horrors. The story of the theater's birth in 1942 and its death two years later is told disjointedly in <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobol </PERSON>'s `` Ghetto'' which opened Sunday at Broadway's Circle in the Square Theater. The play, even with the addition of songs and music, is heavy on philosophic discussion and short on dramatic continuity and character development. That might seem strange, considering the thousands of unspeakable tragedies that occurred in <LOCATION> Vilna </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Sobol </PERSON> is more concerned with historical events than individuals. The events _ some real and some imaginary _ are told in flashback by <PERSON> Srulik </PERSON>, a ventriloquist and the artistic director of the fabled theater. His remembrances make for some striking images but confusing story lines. Director <PERSON> Gedalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Besser </PERSON> captures the audience's attention immediately as Srulik, as an old man, sits on stage in a hospital wheelchair and remembers. Suddenly, the back wall falls, and mountains of bags containing the clothes of dead Jews tumble to the floor as a prison wall topped with barbed wire rises in its place. It's a mesmerizing beginning to the play, and an image that not's topped during the rest of the evening In the ghetto, <PERSON> Srulik </PERSON> carries a ventriloquist's dummy, played by a real actor, <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> is made up to look like the lascivious master of ceremonies in the musical `` Cabaret.'' The dummy is the one occupant of the ghetto who talks back to the Nazi officers, particularly the commandant, <PERSON> Kittel </PERSON>, played with sneering ferocity by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> McHattie </PERSON>. It's <PERSON> Kittel </PERSON> who has the idea for the theater company, and he orders <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gens </PERSON>, the Zionist leader of the Jewish police in the ghetto, to carry it out. The play eventually becomes an argument about the existence of the company between <PERSON> Gens </PERSON> and other members of the ghetto, particularly <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Kruk </PERSON>, founder of the ghetto library. <PERSON> Gens </PERSON> is a practical man who will sacrifice some Jews so others can be saved. If only Jews who work can be kept alive, he will give them jobs in the theater. But <PERSON> Kruk </PERSON> is appalled at the idea and proclaims, `` In a cemetery there can be no theater.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearn </PERSON> as the realistic <PERSON> Gens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jarlath </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> as the more cultured <PERSON> Kruk </PERSON> enunciate their arguments well, but not much is learned about them from the play except their opposite stands on the theater company. <PERSON> Avner </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON>, best known as the clown <PERSON> Avner </PERSON> the Eccentric, plays <PERSON> Srulik </PERSON>. He is n't given much of an opportunity to develop his character, even though the story is told through his eyes. Srulik serves primarily as an excuse for announcing the various excerpts of the company's theatrical productions which are shown only in brief segments. There are a few interesting characters, particularly a cabaret singer played with heart-breaking desperation by <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>. She sings the songs, both original numbers from the ghetto theater as well as new material written by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schimmel </PERSON>, with authenticity. And <PERSON> Donal </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> has some incisive moments as a tailor who helps organize workers to mend German uniforms and which helps keep them alive. <PERSON> Sobol </PERSON>'s play, translated by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lan </PERSON>, never develops dramatically once the ghetto residents establish the theater company. It goes from incident to incident without shedding more light on the characters or why they participated in it. The theater finally was closed down by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in 1944, which the play depicts in a bloody and unsatisfactory finale. Even after more than two and a half hours, the audience is left wondering about the inhabitants of <LOCATION> Vilna </LOCATION>, marveling at their determination to survive, but wanting to know a lot more about what they were really like than `` Ghetto'' manages to tell. In other reviews, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said the presentation is lifeless and is `` aiding rather than combating historical amnesia.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> said the play `` has moments in which harsh images come to life. But for long stretches it is curiously uninvolving.'' <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON>, writing in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, said `` <PERSON> Sobol </PERSON> has theatricalized this fragmentary morality play with great skill.''
</TEXT>
