<HEAD>Jewish Home For Aged Repays Gentile's War Heroism By Admitting Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As a teen-ager in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during World War II, <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Opdyke </PERSON> risked death at the hands of the Gestapo by hiding 12 Jewish friends in the basement and attic of a German officer's villa where she worked All survived the Holocaust, as did countless others who were saved because Mrs. <PERSON> Opdyke </PERSON> shared information overheard from <LOCATION> Gestapo </LOCATION> officers planning roundups in Jewish communities. Last week, an old war debt was repaid. Administrators at the Jewish Home for the Aged in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> community of <LOCATION> Reseda </LOCATION> waived admissions policies and admitted Ms. <PERSON> Opdyke </PERSON>'s 80-year-old husband, <PERSON> William </PERSON>, to their Alzheimer's disease unit. `` We violated all the rules _ he's not from our region, we are sectarian, we are so short of beds _ but there are certain times when there are no rules. This is one of those times,'' Executive Director <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Blumenthal </PERSON> said. `` In caring for <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>, we are repaying a debt to her. We owe her.'' <PERSON> Opdyke </PERSON> is one of only a few non-Jews at the 875-bed facility that provides communal living for old people. Mrs. <PERSON> Opdyke </PERSON>, 68, said she vowed to help her Jewish friends when she saw the way <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s army treated Jews during the 1939 invasion of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. She called it `` a nightmare that changed my life.'' `` I saw a man with a white beard and a little white hat, running carrying a Torah,'' she said. `` Little ones were screaming ` Mama! Mama!' I saw a soldier pull a baby out of its mother's arms and throw him to the ground. Later, I heard shooting. They were killing innocent people.'' While working as a housekeeping for a German major, she hid Jewish friends for nearly eight months, sometimes in the home's attic, other times in the basement Recently, as Ms. <PERSON> Opdyke </PERSON>'s husband began suffering from the advanced stages of Alzheimer's disease, administrators at the Jewish Home for the Aged said they felt a special obligation to care for him. `` She risked her life and this is the return we want to give her,'' said <PERSON> Dena </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the home.
