<HEAD>Eight Dissident Leaders Under Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight leaders of underground political groups remained in custody today, a day after being arrested while selling their magazines on the Arbat pedestrian mall, an activist said. The eight dissidents probably will stay under `` preventive arrest'' through the two-day May Day holiday that ends Tuesday, said <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Mityunov </PERSON>, a member of the self-styled opposition party <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, Express-Chronicle, Free Migration, Debate, and Trust groups were detained Sunday after ignoring police calls to disperse. `` Down with the fascists!'' one man yelled at police as they grabbed the activists. In their publications and in telephone calls to Western reporters, the groups declared Sunday a `` samizdat holiday.'' `` Samizdat'' is Russian for self-published and is used to describe underground newspapers and magazines. On Sunday, the dissidents perched atop concrete planters outside the Vakhtangov theater on Arbat Street, silently holding makeshift bulletin boards bearing copies of their publications. Thousands of onlookers strolled along the mall in the 70 degree weather and peeked at the publications. The most sensational of the newspapers was a copy of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda that had pasted to it cartoons lampooning Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. One cartoon portrayed <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> as a devil. A policeman announced through a megaphone that the gathering was not sanctioned, and he ordered the dissidents to disperse. About 15 minutes later, officers moved in. The Democratic Union, formed in May, seeks multiparty elections, independent trade unions, a new constitution and the withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.
