<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oceanographers have recovered <PERSON> Jason </PERSON>, the errant submersible robot that took a dive last week, but have decided to give its understudy, Medea, the starring role in an underwater show. <PERSON> Jason </PERSON>, a high-tech, propeller-driven submersible equipped with video cameras and maneuverable arms, was retrieved from the bottom of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> on Saturday. It sank 2,100 feet to the ocean floor Wednesday when its cable to the support ship Star Hercules snapped. Meanwhile, the submersible Medea, which was used to recover <PERSON> Jason </PERSON>, was expected to take center stage today as the first of 250,000 students in 12 cities across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> hook up via two-way satellite with marine explorers off the coast of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Over the next two weeks, museum officials and elementary and high school students will watch via satellite as <PERSON> Medea </PERSON> inspects the wreckage of a sunken Spanish galleon. Medea is a six-foot-long, one-ton platform carrying three television cameras, two color and one black-and-white. Unlike <PERSON> Jason </PERSON>, it is not remotely operated with its own propulsion system; it is towed behind a surface craft and its cameras operate as it passes a target. Organizers had hoped <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> would be able to go on with the show, but <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagopian </PERSON> of the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, a sponsor of the program, said <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> will undergo a complete evaluation before returning to service. `` <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> will probably be going back in, but not right away,'' <PERSON> Hagopian </PERSON> said Sunday from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>. `` It could be a matter of just a few days.'' About 2,000 museum officials, teachers and technicians were testing a satellite hookup last week when <PERSON> Jason </PERSON>, the younger brother of the robot that first rummaged through the Titanic's wreckage, unceremoneously sank on its debut mission <PERSON> Hagopian </PERSON> said that while most of the damage to <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> appeared to be cosmetic, technicians planned to run it through a series of tests before returning it to the water. `` I understand that there is minimal damage to it. It is still very usable. It's not bad at all,'' she said. `` On a scale of one to 10, with one being minimal damage, I'd say we're at a one.'' The May 1-14 project's sponsors include <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hole </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>. Participating museums, mostly science and natural history museums, are in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>.
