<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Paraguayans voted today for a president and congress to replace the 34-year regime of Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who was toppled in a Feb. 3 coup. Gen. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, the candidate of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the man who ousted <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, was expected to easily defeat former exile <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laino </PERSON> and six other rivals. The <ORGANIZATION> Colorados </ORGANIZATION> were expected to retain control of congress. <PERSON> Laino </PERSON> denounced election irregularities, such as a lack of indelible ink at some stations to prevent double voting and a voter registration list that favored the ruling party. But he said this morning that some flaws were unavoidable and if fraud was not `` generalized'' his party, the country's second biggest, would accept the results. Voters interviewed shortly after polls opened at 7 a.m. -LRB- 8 a.m. EDT -RRB- said the elections were as free as any they had voted in. Voting was conducted in privacy and the ballots of all eight parties were available, said architect <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Facetti </PERSON>. `` That did n't use to happen'' in the days when Paraguayans were encouraged to vote for <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` Before, I would n't even have talked with you. What if a policeman saw?'' said <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, 57, a retired public accountant. `` Now the atmosphere is completely different.'' Polls indicate <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> will receive as much as 70 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, 76, seized power in a 1954 coup and brooked little opposition during his lengthy rule, arranging to be elected every five years. He was unseated on Feb. 3 and sent into Brazilian exile. The 65-year-old <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> has been hailed by Paraguayans for toppling <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, but opposition parties _ banned under <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> _ have complained they were not given enough time to prepare for today's elections. Eight parties have fielded candidates in the voting for president, 36 senators and 72 deputies to finish the five-year terms begun by <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> and congress following elections in February 1988. The parties are responsible for providing their own ballots and presidential candidate <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> said his opposition <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Febrerista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was not sure its ballots would be available at all of the more than 10,000 polling places nationwide. `` We've distributed our ballots to the main places, but I'm not sure we've gotten through'' to smaller, more remote villages in the nation of 4 million, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has controlled the government for 42 years and <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> has broadened his base by improving relations among its factions as well as with foreign governments and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, to which most Paraguayans at least nominally belong. At a campaign rally Saturday night, <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> repeated his pledge to complete only <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s term and to hand over power in August 1993 to `` my successor, freely elected by the people at the ballot box.'' The opposition contends the <ORGANIZATION> Colorados </ORGANIZATION> will benefit from dated voter registration lists. Even the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> says that up to 600,000 names on the list of 2.2 million may be invalid. The main campaign issue has been who can best move a country that has never had a democratic government in that direction. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> has broadened civil liberties and pledged to reform the constitution, electoral laws and penal code. The polls were to open at 7 a.m. and close at 4 p.m. with unofficial results expected tonight. Paraguayans ages 18 to 60 are required by law to vote. Violators face small fines.
