<TEXT>
 Attackers firing from a passing car today shot and killed anti-apartheid activist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> outside his home, friends said. Police confirmed a white man was killed in a shooting incident at <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>'s home in the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> neighborhood of <LOCATION> Troyeville </LOCATION> but declined to release other details. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, 44, was a lecturer in social anthropology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> and a prominent member of several anti-apartheid organizations. He led campaigns against the government's policy of detention without trial. <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON>, his former wife, told the independent <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> was opening the back door of a van when shots were fired by men in a car. She said he had just returned from buying plants at a nursery. <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, a colleague of <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>'s and a fellow activist, said she was certain the killing was politically motivated. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON>, a former detainee now serving as unofficial spokesman for major anti-apartheid groups, said in a statement: `` We are deeply shocked by this blatant assassination of our dear comrade ... `` We are concerned that his death comes as a result of unflinching opposition to the system of apartheid,'' <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON> said of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of legal race discrimination. `` The only beneficiaries of his death are those who have an interest in perpetuating this evil system.''
