<HEAD>Justices to Study Michigan Campaign Spending Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to restudy, in a case involving the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, what limits should be placed on campaign spending by political groups that incorporate themselves. The court said it will hear an appeal by <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> officials that is supported by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> has about 8,000 dues-paying members, about three-fourths of them corporations. The chamber planned in 1985 to place a paid advertisement in the Grand Rapids Press in support of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandstra </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for the state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>. Fearing the ad would be considered illegal under <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s Campaign Finance Act, the business group filed a federal lawsuit seeking to have the law declared unconstitutional The chamber said the act violates its free-speech rights. The state law generally prohibits corporations from spending in behalf of political candidates and carries a maximum $ 10,000 fine. The law permits a corporation to make such expenditures if it sets up a special fund, or political action committee, that is required to keep records and disclose the names of contributors. The <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> has such a fund. However, it wanted to pay for the newspaper ad for <PERSON> Bandstra </PERSON> out of its general treasury, which is exempt from the record-keeping and reporting requirements of the state campaign finance law. A federal judge ruled that the chamber may not spend money from its general treasury in behalf of a political candidate. The judge said the state campaign finance act, aimed at heading off corruption of the political process, applied to the chamber's activities But the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last September overturned the judge's decision. `` We conclude that indirect expenditures made by a non-traditional corporation, like the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, formed for essentially ideological purposes and to disseminate economic and political ideas and not to amass capital, do not pose the threat or appearance of corruption,'' the appeals court said. The appeals court relied heavily on a 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision limiting the federal government's power to regulate corporate political spending. The justices said then that the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971 violates freedom of speech when applied to corporations formed primarily to influence public opinion, not to make a profit. The high court ruled in favor of a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> group formed to protest the legalization of abortion. The 1986 ruling said corporations formed to promote political ideas, that have no shareholders and are not established by business corporations or labor unions, should not be subject to the federal campaign spending law. The 6th Circuit court said the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> fits that description. The appeals court also said there was no danger the chamber's corporate members will use the business group `` as a conduit for massive undisclosed corporate political spending. Anyone contributing more than $ 100 to a political candidate _ through the chamber or otherwise _ still must file a report disclosing that spending under state law, the appeals court said. In a dissenting opinion, Judge <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Merritt </PERSON> said the ruling allows corporate giants, such as <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, to funnel large sums of money through the chamber to favorite candidates without revealing the spending. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> joined <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> officials in urging the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overturn the appeals court ruling. The decision, if applied to federal law, `` would substantially undermine congressionally mandated limitations upon the use of corporate wealth to influence the outcome of federal elections,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> said. The case is <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1569.
