<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Profits     05-01 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Profits,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Study Goodyear's Use of Foreign Laws to Ease Tax Bite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to hear a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to collect potentially hundreds of millions of dollars in taxes from multinational corporations. In a case involving <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the court said it will review a ruling that allows multinationals to use foreign tax laws to reduce their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxes. The case stems from operations of <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>'s British subsidiary in the early 1970s. The Ohio-based corporation's subsidiary incurred net losses in 1972 and 1973 _ at least under British tax law. The subsidiary's 1973 loss included British tax deductions that were not allowed under American tax law As a result, the British government refunded to the subsidiary the tax payments it made there for 1970 and 1971. The refunds prompted the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to recompute the taxes it said <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> owed in this country. Multinationals are entitled to claim a share of taxes paid by subsidiaries overseas as credits against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxes. In the <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> case, since American law did not recognize the 1973 deductions permitted the company in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> the corporation's loss was converted into a profit. The redetermination had the further effect of wiping out, for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tax purposes, the foreign tax credits previously allowed in 1970 and 1971. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> assessed <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> $ 791,240 in taxes and interest for 1970 and 1971. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> then sued in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, saying the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> erred in applying American law instead of British law to determine the company's accumulated profits. The claims court ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>. But a federal appeals court here reversed the decision last August. The appeals court said a multinational company is entitled to use a foreign nation's tax laws to determine accumulated profits made by a subsidiary in that country. Administration officials said the ruling could have `` enormous importance'' for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tax revenues. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, in the appeal acted on today, said more than 25,000 foreign subsidiaries of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are doing business in more than 100 countries. The government said its most recent figures show the companies claimed more than $ 9 billion in foreign tax credits in 1982. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing $ 150 million in claimed refunds in such cases and expects the appeals court ruling will prompt an additional $ 750 million in refund claims. The government appeal conceded that the impact of the appeals court ruling has been blunted by a 1986 change in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tax law that may mean multinationals no longer will be able to use a foreign country's calculation of its accumulated profits for most future tax payments here. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1474.
