 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today appeared to clear the way for a federal trial against nine current and former <ORGANIZATION> Synanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> figures accused of illegally conspiring to regain the group's tax-exempt status. The justices sent the case back to a federal appeals court for restudy in light of their March 28 ruling that criminal defendants may not immediately appeal a judge's refusal to dismiss an indictment for alleged grand jury abuses by prosecutors. The <ORGANIZATION> Synanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> figures had sought to throw out an indictment that charges them with destroying evidence of violent activities at the California-based organization. The defendants said the 1985 indictment should be dismissed because of prosecutorial misconduct. <ORGANIZATION> Synanon </ORGANIZATION> was founded by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederich </PERSON> some 30 years ago as a non-profit center for rehabilitating drug and alcohol users. In the late 1970s it became embroiled in allegations of violence, threats, and harassment of former members and opponents. <PERSON> Dederich </PERSON> has been accused of converting the organization into a violent cult. In October 1978, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Morantz </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lawyer representing two former <ORGANIZATION> Synanon </ORGANIZATION> members in a suit against <ORGANIZATION> Synanon </ORGANIZATION>, was bitten by a rattlesnake he found in his mailbox. <PERSON> Dederich </PERSON> and two other <ORGANIZATION> Synanon </ORGANIZATION> members pleaded no contest to charges of conspiracy to murder <PERSON> Morantz </PERSON>. The indictment involved in the case acted on today did not name <PERSON> Dederich </PERSON>. But it said nine others, including his daughter, <PERSON> Cecelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederich </PERS