<HEAD>Court Says Indiana Inmate Has Right to Have Suit Tried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today revived an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> prison inmate's lawsuit, ruling unanimously that the suit should not have been automatically ruled `` frivolous.'' The justices said a federal trial judge was wrong in finding <ORGANIZATION> Harry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sr. </ORGANIZATION>'s suit frivolous because it failed to state a claim on which a court could grant <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> some relief. Such a failure to comply with the federal rules of civil procedure does not automatically make a lawsuit frivolous, Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> wrote for the court. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, an inmate at the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> State Reformatory, sued various prison officials in 1986. His complaint said he had been diagnosed by a doctor at the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> as having a small brain tumor that affected his equilibrium and he should be excused from all work details. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' suit said that when he was transferred to the reformatory, doctors refused to treat the tumor and officials assigned him to do garment-manufacturing work. When he refused to continue working, the reformatory disciplinary board responded by transferring him to a less desirable cellhouse. The suit, however, did not allege `` deliberate indifference'' on the part of prison doctors or officials _ a necessary allegation in such cases when prison inmates allege cruel and unusual punishment. The case is <PERSON> Neitzke </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 87-1882.
