<HEAD>High Court Says Lawyers Can't Be Forced In Non-Criminal Federal Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers may not be forced by federal law to represent poor people in non-criminal federal cases, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. By a 5-4 vote, the court ruled in favor of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON>, an attorney from rural <LOCATION> Fairfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, who specializes in business cases. He had refused a federal judge's order to represent prison inmates in a civil rights suit because he said he felt unqualified for the assignment. `` We do not mean to question, let alone denigrate, lawyers' ethical obligation to assist those who are too poor to afford counsel,'' said Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> for the court `` In a time when the need for legal services among the poor is growing and public funding for such services has not kept pace, lawyers' ethical obligation to volunteer their time and skills ... is manifest,'' he said. But <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said the federal law is clear: lawyers may be requested to help _ not forced to do so. The federal law authorizing legal help for poor people in civil cases specifically says a judge may `` request'' any attorney take the case, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> noted. He was joined by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. In a dissenting opinion, Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may have used the word `` request'' but actually meant `` respectfully command.'' `` In my opinion, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave its endorsement to these judicial requests, assuming that it would be unthinkable for a lawyer to decline without an adequate reason,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. He was joined by Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON>, who argued his own case before the high court last February, had been ordered to represent two current inmates and a former inmate at the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> state prison in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>. The inmates said prison guards and officials filed false disciplinary reports against them, physically mistreated them and endangered their lives by revealing they were informants. A federal judge picked <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON> in 1987 to represent them from a list of more than 100 lawyers compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and the state's bar association. In addition to saying he lacked experience in trial work, <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON> said the federal courts do not have power to require an unwilling attorney to represent someone in a civil case. The possible penalties <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON> faced for his refusal to take the prison cases were not discussed. But presumably he could have been held in contempt and fined or even jailed had the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected his appeal. Courts routinely assign lawyers to represent indigent defendants in criminal cases and the lawyers are paid, at taxpayer expense, generally a fraction of what they would receive normally. In civil rights cases, lawyers are paid expenses and may receive a share of any damages won by their clients. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vietor </PERSON> had denied <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON>'s motion to be excused from the inmates' suit. The judge said <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON> was competent and had trial experience. The case is <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1490.
</TEXT>
