<HEAD>Official Says 53 Died in Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOHA, Qatar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flash floods that have struck central <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> since March 19 have killed 53 people and injured 50, it was reported Monday. It was the first official casualty toll cited in the three weeks of intermittent flooding, the worst in years to hit the impoverished <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> state. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Salem </PERSON> <PERSON> Badinar </PERSON>, secretary of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> parliament, told the Qatari newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Raya </ORGANIZATION> that 3,066 houses and 625 miles of roads were destroyed in the flooding. In addition, about 48,000 acres of farm land were inundated, destroying 60 percent of the grain and fruit crop, <PERSON> Badinar </PERSON> said. He did not say how many were left homeless by the floods. Earlier reports from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> put the number of homeless at between 50,000 and 100,000.
