<HEAD>Labor Dept. Proposes $1.15 Million In Fines For Explosion That Killed
Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> today cited two contractors for safety and health violations and proposed $ 1.15 million in fines for a methane gas explosion that killed three workers in a sewer tunnel project. <PERSON> S.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <PERSON> McCook </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, the main contractor for the project, was cited for 68 willful violations carrying fines of $ 680,000 in connection with last November's fatal blast. CH2M <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Corvallis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, hired to supervise the project, was cited for 47 willful violations carrying penalties of $ 470,000. Both companies have 15 days to appeal the citations and penalties to the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Connors </PERSON>, regional administrator of <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office. The proposed fine of $ 10,000 per willful violation was the maximum allowed, <PERSON> Connors </PERSON> said. Willful violations are the most serious issued by <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> and are based on a finding that the contractors knew that a dangerous condition violated safety standards and made no effort to correct it, <PERSON> Connors </PERSON> said. `` These penalties are one of the largest I am aware of for the region and certainly the largest that I am aware of for a tunnel project,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> investigators believe they have located the exact cause of the Nov. 10 explosion but <PERSON> Connors </PERSON> declined to release that information, citing concerns about future litigation. Criminal negligence charges could also be filed against the contractors, he said. The citations accused the two contractors of failing to train workers about the proper response when methane is detected in a tunnel, using inappropriate electrical equipment and wiring methods for a `` gassy'' tunnel, failing to have adequate ventilation for the tunnel, and keeping inadeqauate records of air monitoring in the tunnel. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation concluded that the two contractors were directly responsible for the deaths of the three workers, he said.
