ve and unnecessary.'' `` To investigate if need be, yes. To detain, no,'' he said. The settler, <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Lulu </PERSON>, was released on $ 3,880 bail today after fellow settlers maintained a two-day vigil outside military government headquarters in <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio reported <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Lulu </PERSON> was freed after a hearing before <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> Dalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Koval </PERSON> and quoted her as saying the settler apparently acted in self-defense when he fired his pistol Saturday. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> media reports said he fired after Palestinian youths stoned his car. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Lulu </PERSON> has not been charged, but remains under investigation, police said. <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, a city of 79,000 Palestinians where settlers live in two tiny enclaves, is a frequent site of friction between Jews and Arabs. Most Jewish settlements in the occupied lands are located away from Arab population centers. More than 70,000 settlers live in the occupied lands amid 1.7 million Palestinians.
