<FIRST>r a AM-PetroglyphPark     05-01 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Petroglyph Park,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Field Hearing Considers Proposed Petroglyph Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AQ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM McELROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of prehistoric Indian petroglyphs etched into dark, basalt rock have survived for hundreds and hundreds of years, but time no longer is on their side. The once-remote volcanic ridge they adorn on <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>'s west side is in danger of being swallowed by civilization. `` If we do n't get the federal authorization from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year the pressures of development and vandalism are so intense out there we may be losing the opportunity,'' said <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastvold </PERSON>, a leader in a move to have <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> create a national monument to preserve the carvings of humans and animals. `` It really is the 11th hour.'' Evidence of the threat to the petroglphs is all around the 17-mile escarpment, created by lava flows that began 190,000 years ago. Houses and roads creep closer. One path to the area passes mounds of rubbish. Some drawings have been marred by spray paint or damaged by gunshots. The drawings are the work of early Pueblo Indians who lived in the area between 1300 and 1650 A.D. Spanish settlers arriving the area in the 1500s added their own petroglyphs. `` This is the largest concentration of rock art in the world in a major city,'' said Eastvold. He said preserving the more material elements of a culture such as architecture is not enough. `` The art and religion are what made them live,'' Eastvold said. He said the petroglyphs are even more exciting because they were done by the ancestors of the present Pueblo Indians of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, meaning they still are part of a living culture. Eastvold said the petroglyphs also are artistically appealing. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators, Republican <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON>, have introduced legislation to establish the monument. They conducted an <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> public lands subcommittee hearing Friday in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> to hear from federal, state and local officials, developers, conservationists and Indian leaders. Those who spoke at the hearing indicated support for the monument. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, regional director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said at the hearing that if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> fails to take action within two years the land will become degraded to the point it could no longer be considered for monument status. Eastvold, head of the group <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albuquerque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroglyphs </ORGANIZATION>, said he believes that if the national monument is not created most of the land will be lost to development. `` You would probably end up with little bits and pieces preserved in an inadequate manner,'' he said. The bill introduced by <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON>, and an identical measure introduced in the House by Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiff </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, calls for the national monument to include 7,100 acres. About 4,300 acres of land already is publicly owned. The total value of the land that would have to be acquired is estimated at $ 90 million, with $ 50 million coming from the federal government and the remaining $ 40 million from the city and state. The state and city already have made provisions for a portion of their commitments. In addition to preserving the estimated 15,000 carvings, proponents say the monument would draw 400,000 visitors and generate $ 5 million in revenue for the city and its businesses in the first year alone. <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> believes that what should be stressed is not so much the cost of doing the project but the cost of not doing it because the drawings would continue to be degraded until they are lost forever. <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> agreed. `` I think the longer you go into the future the more important it's going to have been that people at this time took the opportunity to set some land aside and preserve some of these petroglyphs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
