<HEAD>Famed French Wine House Sending Recork Task Force To U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The legendary French wine house Chateau Lafite-Rothschild is sending a task force to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to recork _ at no charge _ older bottles of the fabulously expensive <LOCATION> Bordeaux </LOCATION>. Starting Tuesday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the experts will recork some 2,000 bottles of 1962, or older, vintages. The group also will visit <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. The Lafite team, which was in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> last year, took reservations for the recorking service through next January. The demand, said the company, was `` tremendous.'' An 1806 vintage _ the same year <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> ordered the blockade of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and construction of the <ORGANIZATION> Arc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Triomphe </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> _ will be among the wines to be recorked. A bottle from that year once sold for $ 31,000. `` There is no charge for this service,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chateau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the major Lafite importer in this country. `` The chateau does it as the most remarkable after-sale service in the industry.'' <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> would say only that the 1806 is owned by a collector in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> whose identity he could n't disclose. The recorking is carried out by Lafite because, as the wine experts say, `` wine is only as good as its cork.'' Old corks can become dry, which allows air to seep into the bottle and can cause wine to spoil. Recorking is especially needed for the nobler wines of the world, made with the view that a very good bottle may not reach the most drinkable period for years, even decades and generations. A minimum of 15 years is often recommended before a given vintage of Lafite should be consumed. The 1961 vintage, for instance, was n't ready for drinking until last year _ 27 years. `` As the <ORGANIZATION> Rothschilds </ORGANIZATION> have tended over a century of vintages at Lafite, they have determined that their bottles should be recorked about every 25 years or so,'' said <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>. `` Even the finest cork has limited lifespan, and keeping the cork in good condition is essential to protect the wine.''
