<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Budget cuts forced by voter rejection of a tax package will `` go beyond common sense,'' Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said Monday as the administration studied closing some universities and hospitals. Rejection in Saturday's referendum means the state will have a projected $ 720 million deficit when the new fiscal year begins July 1, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. Even with passage of the package, the administration would have been forced to cut spending by $ 200 million, including reducing a charity hospital to an outpatient clinic and laying off 4,100 state employees, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. `` Now we must go beyond that. The cuts will be deeper than I wanted, deeper than common sense, but we will not do business as usual,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said wearily at an impromptu news conference. The governor referred to projecting oil prices high enough to balance the budget on paper, a routine practice until <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> took office in March 1988. With high oil price projections, the state ended each year with massive deficits which had accumulated to $ 900 million by the time he took over. Each increase of $ 1 a barrel in the price of oil, sustained for a year, means around $ 28 million in extra state tax revenue. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said the state realistically could increase the projection from $ 15 to $ 17 a barrel since the price of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> oil at this time is about $ 18, `` but you're only talking about $ 60 million if we do that.'' The tradition of having oil companies and other big businesses pay a big share of state revenues in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> dates back to the days of populist Gov. <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> in the 1920s and 1930s. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s plan would have shifted the tax burden away from big business, putting more of a load on individuals through the income tax. It would have reduced sales taxes and given businesses incentives to move to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and expand. The plan also included a $ 1.4 billion program to improve highways, airports and shipping ports, funded by a gasoline tax increase of 4 cents a gallon. <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> touted his plan as a way to bring jobs to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, which has the highest unemployment rate in the nation at 9.6 percent, and to end the state's dependence on the oil industry. `` We had a number of -LRB- industrial -RRB- prospects that had anticipated fiscal reform to open new plants,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. `` I had to call them this morning and talk it through. It's not all good news. We'll hang on to what we can.'' The Legislature could extend for another year a temporary suspension of sales tax exemptions on food, drugs and utilities that was put into effect last summer to stave off bankruptcy, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. Allowing that suspension to expire on June 30 would leave a $ 500 million hole in the budget, he said. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said he did n't want to talk about specifics of what universities or hospitals might have to be closed. `` You'll know as soon as we know,'' he said. Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Adley </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a close adviser to the governor, had said earlier in the day that his phone `` was ringing off the hook this morning. They're -LRB- lawmakers -RRB- scared. Reality is setting in and they do n't want to lose institutions in their districts. Meanwhile, state Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, perhaps the most vocal legislative opponent of the tax package, said lawmakers might want to extend sales tax increases to avoid closure of charity hospitals and universities. Throughout the tax referendum campaign, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> said the people `` do n't want any more taxes. None.'' `` I'll hold an olive branch out to him -LRB- the governor -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> Klan leader. `` We've got to solve the financial problems. The Legislature might be willing to restore some of the temporary taxes if it comes to that. We still have some time to play with this thing.''
