 Former arms negotiator <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> criticized the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on Monday for failing to assert leadership and avert an argument raging in the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance over short-range nuclear weapons. `` There has been no American leadership whatsoever,'' said <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON>, and as a result, `` we have a very sharp dispute over a silly issue.'' <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON>, chief arms negotiator for then-President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> stick to agreements reached in the alliance in 1987 and 1988 to modernize <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Lance tactical missiles in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. At the same time, <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> should open negotiations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> about eliminating the entire class of nuclear missiles with ranges of under 300 miles and therefore not subject to the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Force pact, which took effect last year. The dispute over modernizing short-range nuclear weapons has pitted West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> against <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> held what they called frank and intensive talks on the issue Sunday in <LOCATION> Deidesheim </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, but parted in disagreement. `` We still have quite a lot of work to do,'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said after the meeting, although predicting that an agreement was possible before a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATI