<HEAD>Pope Attacks `Contraceptive Imperialism,' Arrives on French Isle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. DENIS, Reunion (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> flew to this French <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> island Monday after urging his flock in the impoverished African nation of <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> to reject `` contraceptive imperialism'' and abortion. The pope arrived on this volcanic island, about 450 miles east of <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>, on the second stop of a nine-day tour that will also take him to the African nations of <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION>. He was greeted at the airport by French Prime Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> and a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> military band playing the Marseillaise. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> then rode in his glass-enclosed popemobile to the municipal building to meet privately with <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> and address political and church officials. He later spoke to local clergy at the 19th century cathedral and had dinner with bishops from Reunion, <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION> and the Seyechelles. Earlier Monday, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> concluded a three-day visit to <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> with an open-air Mass for about 100,000 people in <LOCATION> Fianarantsoa </LOCATION>, a wine-producing town in the south of the island. He devoted much of his homily to birth control, a pressing issue in <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>, where the average citizen earns $ 250 a year and the population of 11 million is growing at an annual rate of 3 percent. Only one in 100 married women in <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> uses contraception, according to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, and Western aid agencies have sought to promote the use of artificial birth control. `` The power to transmit life must be respected,'' said the white-robed pontiff, speaking in French from a wooden altar overlooking a dirt field near the airport. `` You can not let yourselves be won over by the increasing tendency to consider it -LRB- child-bearing -RRB- secondary, or even to want to prevent human fertility from expressing itself.'' The <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said that, if it is necessary for couples to choose family planning, they must follow `` methods that respect nature.'' He was referring to the only method approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, natural family planning based on abstinence during a woman's fertile period. `` The teaching of the church seems difficult. But many couples testify that it is possible to follow it and that it is even a liberation compared to what we call ` contraceptive imperialism.''' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> also decried abortion, saying families must `` respect the life of the child from conception.'' `` Do not accept that abortion is commonplace. Take care of the fragile but human life of the unborn child ... the dignity of man is at stake.'' Before the ceremony, the pope blessed lepers kneeling in the sand at the foot of the altar, patting each of them on the head. They came from a nearby leper clinic founded in 1912 by a Polish Jesuit missionary, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Beyzym </PERSON>. `` I would like to say to those suffering from leprosy and other illnesses ... how much the church wants to bring them consolation and comfort. How much she loves them.'' Addressing officials in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Denis </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> told islanders they should `` rethink certain ways of life.'' He did n't elaborate but local church officials have expressed concern about consumerisim and materialism as well as superstition, exorcism and satanic cults. Reunion, covering 970 square miles, has been a French Overseas Department since 1946. It is the richest of the countries on the pope's trip as a tourist attraction and sugar exporter and also has the highest percentage of Catholics _ 90 percent of the 500,000 population. Seventy percent of its people are descendants of the African slaves brought to the island by the French in the 1600s.
