<HEAD>Rebels Announce Monthlong Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leader of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s southern rebel movement announced Monday a conditional monthlong cease-fire, which he called a goodwill gesture toward ending a six-year civil war. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, a renegade army colonel who leads the rebels, said the unilateral truce will hold only as long as the government carries out no troop movements in the war-torn south. This includes reinforcing beleaguered army forces in the region, he said. There was no immediate government response to his offer, which follows weeks of successes for the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Several government garrisons, including in the largest southern town of <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>, are under severe pressure. In a statement broadcast by clandestine <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> said he has ordered his forces to `` remain in their present positions'' throughout May. Army troops must do likewise, he said, but added a formula could be worked out to allow provision of non-military supplies. `` Our people are suffering. It is our responsibility to end the war,'' he said on the broadcast from <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and monitored in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, the Sudanese capital. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in April began a relief operation to ease a war-induced famine and the flight of potential victims. <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> refused overtures to declare a `` month of tranquillity'' in the south, but he did agree to allow passage of goods through specified corridors. Unidentified attackers twice have ambushed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> food convoys since then. On Monday, ambushers sprayed a vehicle with small arms fire near the rebel-held t