 A white anti-apartheid activist was shot and killed Monday outside his home by an assailant firing from a passing car, police said. Colleagues said they had no doubt that <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, 44, was assassinated because of his political activities. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, a lecturer in social anthropology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and a prominent member of several anti-apartheid organizations, was a leading opponent of the government's policy of detention without trial and held periodic tea parties for the families of detained black activists. Police said <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> died almost instantly after he was hit in the back by a bullet fired from a heavy-caliber weapon outside his home in the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> neighborhood of <LOCATION> Troyeville </LOCATION>. Nothing was known about the assailant, police added With <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> at the time was <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, a friend and fellow member of the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a Johannesburg-based monitoring group established by anti-apartheid activists last year. She said <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> was shot after they had returned from buying plants at a nursery. She said she heard a noise from a passing car which she thought had backfired, then saw <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> stagger and tell her: `` I've been shot with a shotgun. Get an ambulance.'' `` It is clear to me that his killing was a highly professional job,'' she said. `` I find it frightening that those who opposed him were prepared to go to such lengths to eliminate someone.'' Dozens of black activists have been killed in recent years in unsolved murders. The Five Freedoms Forum, a human rights groups with which <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> worked, described Monday's killing as one of the first assassinations of a white activist. `` We are deeply shocked by this blatant assassination of our dear comrade,'' said <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON>, a former detainee who serves as unofficial spokesman for major anti-apartheid groups. `` We are concerned that his death comes as a result of unflinching opposition to the system of apartheid,'' <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON> said. `` The only beneficiaries of his death are those who have an interest in perpetuating this evil system.''
