<FIRST>r i AM-India-Missile     05-01 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Missile,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Abort Missile Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIPUR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists on Monday aborted the launch of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s first medium-range ballistic missile seconds before it was to lift off when computers detected an error in one of the rocket's systems, officials said. One military official said a problem developed in the liquid fuel propellant of the $ 6 million missile and there would have been `` a big disaster'' had the countdown reached zero. It was the second time in 11 days that scientists postponed the test-firing of the missile, which experts say has the capability to carry a nuclear warhead. The postponement was met by cheers and the blowing of conch shells by many of the 12,000 villagers who were temporarily evacuated from their homes around the launch site in this eastern Indian town overlooking the Bay of <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION>. A government statement issued at the remote seaside missile center said the launch was called off when computers detected the data error. `` It is not a major fault,'' said V.S. <PERSON> Arunachalam </PERSON>, scientific adviser to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and head of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s missile program at the launch site. But a military official said scientists detected a leak in the missile's liquid fuel propellant 11 seconds before the scheduled firing. `` Had the scientists counted to zero it would have ended in a big disaster,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. A previous attempt to fire the missile on April 20 was called off because of a snag in the ignition system. Military sources said the missile would likely be dismantled and every part checked before a third attempt is made. Scientists will postpone the launch for at least one week, the sources said. Before the launch, angry residents said prayers and held special ceremonies beseeching Hindu gods and goddesses to prevent the missile from being fired. The villagers fear they will be permanently shifted from their homes if the missile launch is successful and the test range is used for more firings. The 7 -LCB- - ton surface-to-surface missile has a range of 1,550 miles, Indian military experts say Its first stage is boosted by a solid fuel propellant engine and its second stage is powered by a liquid fuel engine. The range is sufficient to hit targets as far as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the west, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in the east, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the north and islands around the equator in the south, Western military officials said. The missile, named `` Agni,'' or `` fire'' in Hindi, can hit any target in neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s longstanding adversary. The two countries have fought three wars in the past 42 years. Defense experts said the one-ton payload capability is more than enough for the missile to carry a nuclear warhead. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has said its nuclear capacity will be used only for peaceful purposes. But Western military experts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> said if <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> ever uses the missile in a war, it might not carry a conventional warhead. `` You need accuracy or a point target if you are using a conventional warhead,'' said one Western analyst, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` But if you are using a nuclear warhead, the exact target does not matter.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> exploded a nuclear device 15 years ago, and Western experts estimate it would take Indian scientists one week to assemble a nuclear device.
