<TEXT>
 Israeli professors Monday protested the 15-month closure of Palestinian universities and called the measure an unwarranted collective punishment that threatens peace efforts. `` Even though closing the universities does n't kill or maim, it causes serious injury to the fabric of any society,'' said <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gavison </PERSON>, a law professor at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` It disturbs life in a way that is far reaching.'' Israeli military authorities closed <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 29, 1987, and by February 1988 had shut the remaining Palestinian universities in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. About 18,000 students are affected. Authorities called the colleges breeding grounds for anti-Israeli protests. But the 1,200 professors from Israeli universities said the closures threatened efforts to find moderate Palestinians with which to negotiate an end to their 16-month uprising. At least 457 Arabs and 18 Israelis have died in clashes, mostly in the occupied territories. `` Universities are the only place the moderate elements of the Palestinian community can develop,'' said <PERSON> Hava </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazarus-Yafeh </PERSON>, a professor of Asian and African studies at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Otherwise Palestinian leaders grow in prisons ... and leaders who grow in jail tend to be more violent,'' she said. State-run primary and secondary schools in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> have also been closed for all but a few weeks since Feb. 4, 1988. Kindergarten, first - and second-grade classes in some private schools were allowed to reopen earlier this year Authorities barred home study for university students and refused to allow them to use college facilities such as laboratories or libraries, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kretzmer </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor. Recently, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> university was refused permission to open its Library, he said. `` It is hard to understand how opening a library to librarians could endanger security,'' <PERSON> Kretzmer </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s Ms. <PERSON> Gavison </PERSON> called the closures a `` far-reaching collective measure.'' `` Necessary security measures should be taken not against institutions but against those individuals who have may have violated order,'' she said. The longterm closures violate international statutes, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, which governs the treatment of people under occupation, <PERSON> Kretzmer </PERSON> said. He said that a 1982 Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling determined military closures of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> schools could not surpass a reasonable period.
