<HEAD>Paper Blisters Soviet Labor Unions on May Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet trade unions serve to promote the government and the status quo instead of workers' rights, a newspaper said Monday in an article that injected some criticism of official bodies into May Day's labor pageantry. Under the headline `` What do we need a union for?'' economist <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Auzan </PERSON> compared the country's unions to a grandmother `` who makes a lot of fuss, interferes in everything, but who no one really listens to.'' The trade unions have been turned into `` a government maidservant concerned not with defending the interests of the workers, but only with maintaining peace and quiet and an imitation of ` mass support,''' <PERSON> Auzan </PERSON> wrote in Socialist Industry, the Soviet daily. Many Western unions long have said their Soviet counterparts have been co-opted by the government. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urged labor unions in 1987 to be more vigorous in defending rank-and-file workers. But increasing numbers of critics say the unions should prod bureaucrats more aggressively to improve housing, salaries and working conditions. Although some Soviet labor officials acknowledge failings of their unions, they have publicly ruled out forming independent trade organizations like <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s Solidarity. In his article, <PERSON> Auzan </PERSON> said unions should be given more independence and suggested they be decentralized. Unions should act as information clearing houses on vacancies and dislocated workers, set up retraining centers, and guarantee unemployment benefits, the economist said. He also called for union representatives elected to a new national <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies to press for a strike law to clarify what job actions are legal. In his criticisms of unions, <PERSON> Auzan </PERSON> said union leaders never `` fly urgently to the scene of a strike conflict or act as mediators between workers and government organs.'' Even though most strikes are prohibited, there have been increasing reports of workers walking off their jobs to demand higher pay or to protest working conditions. The economist also complained that membership in trade unions is `` practically universally obligatory,'' and he said many bookkeepers automatically deduct union dues from the salaries even of non-members. `` Enough of paying tribute to the union bureaucracy!'' he wrote.
