<HEAD>FDA Panel Recommends Approval of AIDS Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> advisory committee on Monday recommended approval of an aerosolized version of a drug that helps prevent a life-threatening pneumonia in AIDS patients. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is expected to follow the recommendation and approve an aerosol version of pentamidine within weeks, said an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> source who spoke on the condition of anonymity. Aerosolized pentamidine has been widely available to AIDS patients since the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> in February allowed its distribution to be expanded as an experimental medication under government review. However, many insurance plans do not cover experimental drugs. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval would allow nearly universal reimbursement for AIDS patients using the drug. The advisory committee recommended approval of aerosolized pentamidine for preventing initial and recurring bouts of pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, which causes an estimated 60 percent of AIDS deaths. Pentamidine was approved five years ago for use as an injectable drug to treat those already suffering from pneumocycstis. The spray version would make it easier to take into the lungs where the pneumonia infection first shows up. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> estimated that 50,000 patients with AIDS could benefit from the treatment. The recommendation was based largely on data collected from a recent clinical trial conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consortium </ORGANIZATION>, a group of physicians who treat AIDS patients. The trial, which compared the safety of different doses of aerosolized pentamidine, found that the drug `` did not provide complete protection, but did significantly reduce the incidence of this pneumonia,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> LyphoMed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Rosemont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, the leading supplier of injectable pentamidine, is asking to be licensed to supply the aerosol version.
