<HEAD>Prisoners Riot to Protest Jail Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prisoners rampaged through two cell wings of a jail Monday, and dozens conducted a rooftop protest of living conditions, prison officers reported. The <PERSON> Risley </PERSON> remand center, designed to hold just over 500 men in single cells, now accommodates 600 men and 140 women awaiting trial. It is near <LOCATION> Warrington </LOCATION>, 10 miles east of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> on the northwest coast. Trouble began Sunday night when 17 prisoners tried to overpower guards who were unlocking cells in B wing for an exercise period, authorities said. Scores of men wrecked furniture and water pipes. A similar incident began in D wing Monday when it was announced that visits would be canceled because of the violence, officials said. They said B wing was under control Monday night but up to 40 inmates remained on the roof of D wing. Several who hurled objects from the roof at prison officers wore hoods to hide their faces. Three cell areas were wrecked and both wings were flooded by water from the broken pipes, said <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, chairman of the <PERSON> Risley </PERSON> branch of the Prison Officers' Association. Four guards suffered minor injuries to fingers or ribs but no prisoners were injured, he said. Two guards locked themselves in a second-floor cell when the prisoners broke out, their colleagues said. Rioters tried to enter the cell to get at the men, but other officers rescued them by breaking through an outside wall with sledgehammers, they said. Banners on the roof repeated common complaints about conditions in the jail. A report last year by the Inspector of Prisons described conditions at <PERSON> Risley </PERSON> as `` squalid and barbarous.'' The investigation was conducted after seven suicides were reported at the jail in 18 months. Several prisoner protests, including rooftop demonstrations, have occurred since. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said 250 inmates were moved from <PERSON> Risley </PERSON> to