<HEAD>Sir John Boyd, Former Union Leader, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON>, a miner's son who fought off leftists to lead the powerful British union of engineering workers, has died. He was 71. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> died Sunday at his home in <LOCATION> Eastbourne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sussex </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said. A chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1967, he was knighted in 1979. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> started his career as an engineering worker but began work as a trade union organizer in 1946. He stepped up to the presidency of the <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> in 1964. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> spent years fighting communists and left-wing elements for control of the 1.5 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Amalgamated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>. From 1975 to 1982, he served as general secretary of the union, which is one of the largest in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. It includes jobs ranging from professional electrical engineers to manual workers such as mechanics. He believed that the well-being of workers is tied to the health of the economy. `` We no longer represent a hungry mob of people crying out for bread,'' he once said, adding that union members `` know that if our economy breaks down, they will break down with it.'' From 1967 to 1975, <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> sat on the general council of the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the national organization of unions. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> was a director of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> from 1981-86. He was married and had two daughters. No information on funeral services was immediately available.
