<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A paper lunch tray might cost 5 cents more than a plastic model that harms the environment, but students who rid their schools of plastic trays said Monday it was worth a nickel to help save the Earth. Several <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Milford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> students told of their successful anti-plastics battle at <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. They appeared before hundreds of students at a daylong forum sponsored by the U.N. Environment Program. `` Our battle cry was, ` Put your money where your mouth is,''' said 15-year-old <PERSON> Tanja </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogt </PERSON>, who launched the campaign. A majority of the students at <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Macopin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> agreed with her and paid an extra nickel for their cafeteria lunches to be served on cardboard trays. The campaign against polystyrene products began when the teen-ager, inspired by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Paine </PERSON>'s revolutionary pamphlet `` Common Sense,'' wrote a civics paper calling for their ban. Environmentalists say the products, unlike paper, take many years to break down. `` In October, I read an article in our local paper that stated despite threats to all life, the -LRB- school -RRB- board continues to use polystyrene trays in the school cafeteria,'' she said. `` The reason given was pure economics. Paper trays cost 5 cents more than polystyrene. `` I was disgusted. I knew the environment was worth an extra nickel, and I was very confident that my peers would agree,'' she said. For one week last autumn, the schools gave the students a choice: pay $ 1.20 for lunch on plastic, or $ 1.25 for a meal on a paper tray. Seventy-two percent of the high school students and 86 percent of the middle school students paid the extra nickel for paper trays. The <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> voted in December to stop purchasing polystyrene for the township's schools, effective Feb. 1. The students have launched a letter-writing campaign to persuade every school in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> to abolish the use of foam plastics. <PERSON> Kurtiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneid </PERSON>, 16, said the success of the anti-plastics campaign led to formation of a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Milford </LOCATION> ecology club and to new initiatives. `` I personally visited our local McDonald's dressed as <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> McToxic </PERSON> to emphasize our opposition to foam packaging,'' he said.
