<HEAD>Soviet Dissident Predicts Bloodshed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leading Soviet dissident, dismissing <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s reform campaign as a one-sided attempt to save a failed system, predicted on Monday that President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policies will lead to `` a terrible clash ... bloodshed of huge proportions. But turmoil inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could lead <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to release its grip on such eastern European nations as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON> told a forum of democratic leaders from around the world. <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON>, who was jailed and sentenced to internal exile in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, then released in 1976 after an international campaign on his behalf, now heads the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> in the U.S.S.R, a New York-based human rights group. He spoke before the annual conference of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, which brought to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> advocates of democracy from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to present report cards on what many of the speakers called `` a universal democratic revolution.'' The endowment is a U.S.-financed, private-sector attempt to foster democracy as an alternative to totalitarian and authoritarian regimes. Speaking at the forum in the meeting room of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON> contended that in spite of the widespread impression that genuine reform is taking place in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, `` the politburo has not moved toward democracy.'' `` Perestroika is no attempt to establish a free market economy,'' <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON> said. `` Glasnost does not mean the same as freedom of speech.'' `` This is an attempt to square a circle, to find a form of socialism that can survive,'' he said. `` But you can not square a circle.'' <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON> predicted `` a terrible clash in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> between the people and the government, bloodshed of huge proportions.'' He said the process has already started with the bloody suppression of demonstrations in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and the arrest of nationalists in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Citing what he said are other signs of a crackdown, <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON> added: `` The good news is that when there is turmoil in the Soviet system, some countries like <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> may have a chance to get out.'' He said the West is confused about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his aims and mistakenly wants to help him with economic credits. Instead, he said, the West should be supporting the democratic opposition inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> because `` the more cohesive and organized the opposition is, the less likely the government is to repress it.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>, D-Calif., said it is clear to him there is a `` new element'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership, which is `` prepared to make major compromises. `` We've got to deal with them,'' <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> said. `` We are trying to urge them to establish a social compact with all elements of their own society.'' But <PERSON> Bukovsky </PERSON> replied the West is `` doing nothing'' to help the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s democratic forces. He asserted that billions of dollars of economic credits, mostly from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, are flowing into the Kremlin's coffers. `` This will prop up the Soviet regime and help them not to reform,'' he said. He suggested that the West allocate 10 percent of any credits given to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to democratic forces there.
