<HEAD>Airlift Taking Tens of Thousands of Expatriates Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of expatriate Senegalese and Mauritanians flew to their homelands Monday in an airlift aimed at ending a wave of violence that has left hundreds dead. About 55 Mauritanians were reported killed Friday and Saturday in <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION> and the provinces by angry Senegalese seeking revenge for the deaths of hundreds of their countrymen in neighboring <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> earlier last week. Unconfirmed reports said as many as 400 Senegalese were killed April 24-25 in <LOCATION> Nouakchott </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>'s capital, in a wave of violence that began over a land dispute. <LOCATION> Nouakchott </LOCATION> is 375 miles north of <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION>. States of emergency and curfews were in effect in both West African nations' capitals, but vandalism continued in <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION>. The French news agency Agence France-Presse reported bands of pillagers attacked the shops of some Lebanese merchants after all Mauritanian-owned shops were burned or vacated. Officials said the airlift, which started in full Sunday, had carried about 8,720 Senegalese home from neighboring <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> by midday Monday and about 5,785 Mauritanians back home from <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> were assisting in the airlift. Planes were making an average of four round trips per day, airport officials said. Among the Senegalese brought back from <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>, some had their sex organs or limbs mutilated, and most of the corpses brought home had been decapitated, reporters said. Senegalese officials began a program to integrate the returning citizens and provide measures to fill the vacuum created by the departure of the Mauritanians, who ran 80 percent of the small businesses in this country. `` Absolute priority is being accorded to the distribution of basic foodstuffs in <LOCATION