<HEAD>Gore Bill Would Regulate Chemicals that Hurt Ozone Layer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer products that release chemicals into the air which `` rip up the earth's protective ozone layer'' would be regulated and those with non-essential uses would be phased out under legislation introduced Monday by Sen. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s bill is aimed at products ranging from leaking automobile air conditioners to noise horns to some types of fire extinguishers <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> also introduced separate legislation to phase out, within five years, the most dangerous ozone-destroying chemicals and to impose a manufacturer's tax on them. An Ozone Layer Conservation Trust Fund would be established to find alternatives to such chemicals as chloroflurocarbons and halon which have been shown to deplete the ozone layer of the stratosphere. `` We know that these chemicals are ripping up the earth's protective ozone layer and contributing to the greenhouse effect,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said in a statement `` We know that if we immediately stopped all use, the problems they've already created would linger on for decades,'' he said. `` Hesitation simply can not be tolerated. We must move as quickly as possible to stop the destruction.'' He said that `` simple, common sense solutions'' are available now for application every day. `` For example, changing the way we service automobile air conditioners, labeling and eventually stopping the production of non-essential consumer products such as noise horns or party streamers or certain cleaning fluids,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legislation can serve as a catalyst for efforts to eliminate the threat to the ozone layer by nations around the world. `` My purpose is to sound an alarm loudly and clearly _ of imminent and grave danger _ and to describe a strategy for confronting this crisis with changes in our collective behavior and thinking which, if made, can forestall and prevent the horrendous prospect of an ecological collapse,'' he said.
