 At least 25 imprisoned Tamil rebels overpowered Indian soldiers guarding a jail in northern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> on Monday and escaped with weapons and ammunition, residents said. Residents and witnesses to the breakout at <LOCATION> Vavuniya </LOCATION> town, 135 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said other Tamils apparently created a diversion by firing at a nearby Indian sentry post. An <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman could not confirm the break, the first by Tamil separatists since Indian troops began peacekeeping operations in 1987. The spokeswoman can not be identified under briefing rules. In other violence: _ Ambushers thought to be Sinhalese exploded a mine under a passing police patrol jeep in <LOCATION> Polonnawara </LOCATION> and then fired automatic weapons, killing four policemen and wounding two, military officials said The town is 100 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The officials can not be identified under briefing rules. _ Three gunmen believed to be Tamil rebels killed <PERSON> Mutthiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Panchalingam </PERSON>, 52, the senior administrator of <LOCATION> Jaffna </LOCATION> district, in a village outside <LOCATION> Jaffna </LOCATION> town, 185 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, military officials said <PERSON> Jaffna </PERSON> has been headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, a rebel group spearheading the separatist campaign that has claimed 10,000 lives. But a Tamil Tiger leader in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, denied the group was responsible for <PERSON> Panchalingam </PERSON>'s death A senior Tiger leader is holding talks with the government to end the separatist war. Previous government peace overtures to Tamil rebels touched off a violent backlash by Sinhalese militants, who complained that offers made in the India-sponsored peace accord of July 1987 conceded too much to the Tamils and who then launched their own agitation against the government. Sinhalese form 75 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and dominate the government and the military. Tamils make up 18 perecent and claim they are discriminated in jobs and education by the Sinhalese. Indian soldiers are deployed in the island's north and east to enforce the 1987 accord and disarm Tamils who have fought for six years for a separate nation.
