<BYLINE>For Release Wed PMs, May 3 and Thereafter ^Playwright Scores Repertory
Hit with `Nothing Sacred' ^By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> does n't hesitate to confess his amusement and elation at his success in his chosen field of drama. `` I just laughed out loud on the subway,'' he said, recalling a recent ride in his hometown of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. `` I'm a playwright _ and I have children to support.'' He laughed again. The bearded, 41-year-old <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> never has had as successful a year as the past one, with `` Nothing Sacred'' a staple on the repertory theater circuit from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' Mark Taper Forum to the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. Time magazine named it one of the 10 best plays of 1988, although it has yet to be performed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The play is his 18th, yet <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> recalled that when his first play was produced it was only the second play he had ever seen. `` I was just attracted to the idea that you could fill it up any way you want,'' he said to explain his attraction to the theater. The jovial, soft-spoken <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> for the opening of `` Nothing Sacred,'' in a production very similar to its <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> origin, at <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s modern <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> keeps the 19th century Russian setting for his version of <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Turgenev </PERSON>'s `` Fathers and Sons,'' but insists that it now is very much a modern, Canadian work. He first read the original when he was 17 and said he thinks he was in a bit of a trance when he wrote his version. `` I never meant it to be an adaptation,'' he said over lunch before opening night in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. `` I wrote it in 10 to 11 days.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> wanted to bill the play as `` inspired by <PERSON> Turgenev </PERSON>,'' but then decided that would be `` hokey.'' `` Mostly I thought, ` if I just let it come through me, so the language would be, without being forced, for actors living now.''' Literature was the starting point for `` Nothing Sacred'' just as other inspirations have come from something read in the newspaper or a conversation with a friend. `` I'm sure if <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> were alive, he'd be on my side,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said about criticism of his adaptation. Much of his earlier work was of a more eccentric tone, in line with his development in the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> alternative theater scene of the'70s. The appeal of the theater, he said, is its access, that the multimillion dollar budgets required for movies generally are not needed to create plays. Thinking back 12 or 15 years to his early career, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> again laughed at the contrast to the days when the crowds were smaller and the theaters less established. `` When you're used to seeing 200 or 300 people come in, and then you see 800 or 900,'' he joked. `` Where are we going to put them all?'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> agent, <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON>, astutely pitched `` Nothing Sacred'' last year to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> repertory theaters, and there's been some sniping that the success has as much to do with the politics of regional theater as it does with the play. Time, reviewing the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> production, said he `` persuasively makes the debate among student anarchists in 1860s <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> echo that among Marxist collegians of 1960s <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> gave a decidedly mixed review to the production of `` Nothing Sacred'' at <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stage </LOCATION>, saying <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> assumed too much artistic license for a project that could have used a bit more reverence. On the other hand, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> believes it's time for the dominant role of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> reviews to be re-evaluated in light of the changing theater scene that is less concentrated on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. The playwright also said many Canadians gripe about the lack of knowledge in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> about their country, but he chalked that off to a result of Americans' self-preoccupation. `` They do n't know <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is up here feeling insecure about its culture,'' he said. `` They -LRB- Americans -RRB- are generous: ` Come in. Be one of us.' I've never felt, ` you intruder.' It's kind of positive in its own way.'' Some comment has been made that <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> is an example of a classic Canadian case, of gaining legitimacy at home only after being discovered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But he believes his steady career in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> was quite established before productions started of his plays in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> theaters. `` I think the message Canadians always had was that we did n't need to develop our own,'' he said, recalling the days when Canadian theater was dominated by imports from Broadway or <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> `` Somewhere along the line you go, ` Hey, wait. I can do that too.''' And, for those Canadians who did n't hear about him until `` Nothing Sacred'' appeared on <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s Top 10 list, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said simply: `` That's OK. I read Time.''
