<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The story of four single women who look for the perfect prince but have to kiss a lot of frogs along the way is the latest hit comedy movie in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The movie also blasts others in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s young social scene, from yuppies who marry only for tax breaks to far-out leftist activists. The movie `` <PERSON> Beim </PERSON> naechsten <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> wird alles anders'' -LRB- `` With the Next Man Everything Will Be Different'' -RRB- is based on a best-selling book of the same title by writer <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, who has also published collections of satirical cartoons. The film, released in January, was rated No. 5 on the hit movie list published by the Hamburg-based weekly magazine <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> in its March 2 issue. That made `` <PERSON> Beim </PERSON> naechsten Mann'' the second-highest ranked West German movie on the list after `` Herbstmilch,'' the poignant tale of a young Bavarian farm woman during the Nazi era. Movies focusing on women are still unusual in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, despite the success in recent years of woman directors such as <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Doerrie </PERSON>, whose 1985 film `` Maenner'' -LRB- `` Men'' -RRB- was an international hit. The heroine of the movie is <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON> <PERSON> Wechselburger </PERSON>, a film student who sees herself as intellectual, political and prominent in the feminist movement, even though she spends most of her time hunting for men. The film opens with a chaotic battle between <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON> and her boyfriend, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, a young doctor whom she eventually dumps for allegedly being both bourgeois and cheap. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> criticizes <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON> for her wastefulness, cutting open a discarded toothpaste tube with a scalpel to show there was enough toothpaste left for several more brushings. <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON> is quick to retaliate. `` This is what I think of your cheap Christmas present,'' she yells, flushing her own gift to <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, an expensive watch, down the toilet. <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON> confides her troubles to her girlfriends over numerous glasses of wine, most frequently in a local bar called the Cafe Kaputt. `` I'm looking for a relationship that is built on an intellectual basis, not a material one,'' she says. She also insists on `` emotional freedom,'' rejecting marriage as a bourgeois institution. Ironically, she lands in the arms of a married man. Film instructor <PERSON> Gottfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Schachtschnabel </PERSON>, a veteran of the 1960s student revolts, sports a three-day beard and pretentious leftist political attitudes. He, too, rejects the notion of marriage, but does n't bother getting divorced. He `` forgets'' to inform his girlfriends about his status, and defends himself when he's caught. `` <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> was married, too. And he had an affair with his housekeeper. We can only learn from that,'' he tells <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON>. There's also <PERSON> Sieglinde </PERSON>, a social-climbing dental assistant whose yuppie boyfriend marries her for tax savings; the old-fashioned <PERSON> Birgit </PERSON>, who looks for her dream man in the want ads; and <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>, a psychologist who also falls prey to <LOCATION> Schachtschnabel </LOCATION>. It's a film with which West Germans can apparently both laugh and identify. `` The characters may be cliches, but everybody recognizes a few things that are true in real life, aspects he can relate to,'' <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON> of the film's Berlin-based production company said in a recent interview. Although the film focuses on women and the title indicates disappointment with men, it is not just a work for feminists, she said. `` The story is really about curiosity, not disappointment,'' <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON> said. `` Both men and women are often bored with what they have and think another relationship would be better. But, as the film shows, that is n't always the case.'' By the end of the film <PERSON> Constanze </PERSON> succumbs to bourgeois society and gets married after all. She chooses <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, deciding that thriftiness is not the worst vice in the world.
