<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv for Fri AMs May 5 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Group to Help Gamblers Formed in Spain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD LORANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Melgarejo </PERSON> is trying to cool the fever in a country where gambling is a major sport, musical slot machines abound and nearly everyone takes a flyer on <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gordo </LOCATION>, the fat Christmas lottery. His shoestring version of Gamblers Anonymous is called the <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recovering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamblers </ORGANIZATION>. The telephone has been ringing constantly since he mentioned the number on a radio program and told listeners with gambling problems to call. In the four months since, he says, the membership has grown from nearly zero to more than 200. An estimated 50,000 addicted gamblers live in and around the capital. `` It's hang up, answer, hang up, answer,'' said <PERSON> Melgarejo </PERSON>, a reformed gambler who blamed the addiction for ruining his first marriage. He interrupted the interview at a temporary office in a <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> Roman Catholic church to talk with a middle-aged woman who walked in off the street to confess an addiction to slot machines. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has 420,000 `` habitual gamblers,'' 3 percent of the adult population, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gambling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. They are caught in a tradition that goes back at least to 1763, when <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> started the world's longest-running public lottery. `` The difference between ` habitual gamblers' and ` addicts' is basically a semantic one,'' said <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendioroz </PERSON>, head of gambling commission. Spaniards placed $ 29 billion in bets last year, according to the commission. It regulates state-run lotteries and sports pools, and casinos, bingo halls and slot machines, which were legalized in 1977 after a 53-year ban. <PERSON> Mendioroz </PERSON> said the government's take from lotteries, pools and fees last year was more than $ 2.2 billion. Press reports say <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> ranks second in the world in gambling expenditures per capita, behind the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and ahead of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mendioroz </PERSON> says there are `` no reliable figures, but because of the slot machines in bars and restaurants gambling is omnipresent.'' Slots, which blare bits of music as reminders of their presence, are found in 80 percent of the more than 200,000 bars and cafes, commission figures indicate. <PERSON> Mendioroz </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has 310,000 of the machines. One sure sign of a gambling problem, he said, is that 8,000 people have asked his commission not to let them into casinos and bingo halls. He described the number as surprisingly high considering the custom in this Roman Catholic country of hiding such failings. `` Gambling is considered a vice, almost a sin, and the person who has that problem is very reluctant to admit it,'' he said. <PERSON> Melgarejo </PERSON>, a 44-year-old insurance agent, devotes much of his time to unpaid missionary work with gamblers. He says 18 years of gambling cost him his first wife, `` 10 or 12 jobs'' and about $ 217,000. Last year he spent three months at the <ORGANIZATION> Cordoba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recovering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamblers </ORGANIZATION> and managed to conquer the habit. His organization and the original self-help group in <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> are the only two in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Melgarejo </PERSON> said a national federation may result if enough others are formed. He believes the Spanish character encourages gambling. `` It's like <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Quixote </PERSON>,'' he said. `` The Spaniard ... is a romantic. He believes in fantasy, in destiny. He thinks he can solve a lifetime's worth of problems with one stroke of luck.'' End Adv PM Fri May 5
