<HEAD>$Adv 08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, May 8 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Story of Spanish-language Radio Pioneer Told in New Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With about 200 stations now programming in Spanish to the tune of $ 176 million in advertising revenue last year, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Hispanic radio is booming. But the sound was n't always sweet, as seen in the new film, `` Break of Dawn.'' The movie, released in selected Southwestern cities, re-creates the story of <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> radio pioneer <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, who was imprisoned after his on-air protests of Depression-era deportations of Mexicans. `` It's a story about justice prevailing over injustice,'' said producer <PERSON> Jude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Eberhard </PERSON>. Set in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in the 1920s and'30s, the film tells how <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> was paroled after being sent to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION> on trumped up rape charges following his advocacy broadcasts. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> parlayed his musical talents and eye for business into a popular Spanish-language radio program. But it ended when he was sent to prison on charges that were later recanted by the woman who had allegedly been raped. Mexican recording star <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, portraying him as he first translates radio commercials into Spanish, then sings with his guitar and, finally, pays a station for early morning airtime. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and his wife sold advertising on the show, making a profit on the difference. Called `` Los Madrugadores'' -LRB- `` The Early Risers'' -RRB-, the Los Angeles-based program developed a strong following among Hispanics with a mix of live music, discussion of issues and commercials. Now 94, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> lives with his wife, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and was a consultant for the film, said <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Artenstein </PERSON>, who wrote and directed the movie. To insure realism, <PERSON> Artenstein </PERSON> used both Spanish and English dialogue. `` You ca n't have <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> talking and singing in English if you say he was the first -LRB- radio broadcaster -RRB- in Spanish,'' said <PERSON> Artenstein </PERSON>. But the bilingual approach can pose distribution problems. <PERSON> Eberhard </PERSON> said exhibitors are shying away from the film because they do n't know whether to market it as an English or Spanish movie. `` It's scary for the distributors because of the natural language flow,'' she said. Though he changed some characters' names, <PERSON> Artenstein </PERSON> said that all of the film's main roles are based on real people, including an activist <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> consul, a district attorney who helps frame <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, and a teen-age girl who falsely accuses <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> of raping her. Courtroom testimony in the film is taken from <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' trial transcripts unearthed by a law library archivist. <PERSON> Artenstein </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' Spanish-language daily, La Opinion, also had extensive coverage of <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' case, but the English-language media did not have one story. `` Break of <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON>,'' which was shot for $ 850,000, also stars <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Rojo </PERSON> as <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' wife. Others in the film include <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Plana </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON> <PERSON> Serna </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kamala </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Valarie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wildman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Socorro </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>. The film was independently produced by San Diego-based <ORGANIZATION> Cinewest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> is now the nation's largest Hispanic media market, with $ 32.7 million spent on Spanish-language radio advertising in 1988, according to Hispanic Business magazine. Seven radio stations and two television stations now air Spanish broadcasts full time in the city. It is a far cry from the days when <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and his wife had to pay stations in advance for pre-dawn airtime.
</TEXT>
