<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv02   05-01 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 02,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday, May 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Stock List From Main Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock lists are forever offered from Wall Street, one of the reasons being that Wall Street and its institutions and brokers have an increasingly shorter time horizon and an ever-changing focus. Here's a list that's different. It's from Main Street, prepared by serious amateurs who believe in fundamental analysis rather than hunches, and long-term investing rather than short-term trading. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has just released its Top 100 stocks, which it says is made up of the most widely held companies among individual investors and investment clubs around the country. Heading the list are <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PepsiCo </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, four of which were also in the top five a year ago. The newcomer, <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, jumped from 16th place. Advancing the furthest, suggesting individual and club investors believe the shares have good long-term futures, were <ORGANIZATION> Rollins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION>, from 80 to 34; <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION>, from 92 to 51; and <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>, at 31 a newcomer to the list. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Janke </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION> president, observes that while the market's horizon seems to be getting shorter and its turnover greater, and that many stocks seem to be chosen because of publicity, the <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION>'s membership sticks to long-term Fundamental to its investment concept is that company performance should be studied thoroughly before any commitment is made, and that the investment should be made primarily in companies growing more rapidly than the economy. In operating a portfolio, it believes that regular investments, even if in small amounts, are necessary in order to offset the unpredictable ups and downs of the market, and that dividends should be reinvested. The effectiveness of that approach has been demonstrated in learned theses and simple comparisons, but most effectively in the lives of club members who have paid tuitions, bought homes, taken trips and retired on their investments. <PERSON> Janke </PERSON> said a review of 1,600 responses _ <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION> has 135,000 members _ identified at least two significant trends about individual investing habits. First, he said, amateur and individual investors are taking their investing even more seriously than in the past, placing more emphasis on facts and fundamentals rather than on hearsay or gossip. A developing trend, according to <PERSON> Janke </PERSON>, is the growing use of dividend reinvestment plans to help build club holdings and keep commission costs low. More than one-quarter of clubs appeared to be using such plans, he said. Close to a thousand companies offer reinvestment plans, in which dividends are transferred to the shareholder's account with the company. In addition, most plans allow additional monthly or quarterly amounts to be sent directly to the company, thereby eliminating or greatly reducing brokerage costs. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, comments that the disciplined, fundamentalist, long-term perspective of members is often made difficult by the media and professional and institutional investors. He claims the media and professional investors, whom he described as `` the herd on the street'' and the `` flock on the block,'' promote the notion of in-out trading and distract from fundamental considerations. `` Wall Street changes its opinion on stocks many times more often than the real long-term fundamentals of the underlying companies change,'' he said in an analysis of the Top 100 in `` Better Investing,'' <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly magazine. Copies of the report are available at $ 2 from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 1515 <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eleven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> 48067. Annual membership of $ 31 includes the magazine and the <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION> Investors Manual.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday, May 2</NOTE>
