<SECOND>BC-APN--War's Legacy-III, ADV 14-1st Add^,1054</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun., May 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>HA SON BINH, Vietnam: communist authorities.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Over the years, <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON> has been promoted from captain to colonel, his wife, <PERSON> Marian </PERSON>, has turned 55, and his five children have grown up, including one son who was ordained a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priest. While authorities say his official status as <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s only POW in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> is symbolic of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> determination to make sure every MIA is accounted for, his wife believes he is still alive and waits for his return, cherishing the memory of their first meeting on the tennis courts in <LOCATION> Owensboro </LOCATION> when she was 13 and he was 14. `` I think God gives all of us a cross to bear,'' says Mrs. <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has repeatedly denied it is holding live American prisoners or is storing in morgues the remains of MIAs, returning them when it suits its political purposes. `` We have not been able to prove anyone is still alive, but given the information we continue to receive, we can not rule out or ignore that possibility, so we are going to continue to pursue the issue,'' says Lt. Col. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Pentagon. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has received more than 1,100 firsthand reports of sightings of live Americans. In 63 percent of the cases, <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> says, the Americans had been in <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> but had returned home and are not missing in action. Twenty-one percent were fabrications. The other 16 percent are under continuing investigation. Can says some Vietnamese people have been giving out false information on POWs and trafficking in <ORGANIZATION> MIA </ORGANIZATION> remains by digging up Vietnamese graves and trying to pass them off as the remains of Americans in the mistaken belief that they will be rewarded with entry into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` What good is it for us to keep one or two American MIA prisoners?'' asks Can. `` What good is it for us to hold remains if we return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> nearly 600 POWs. Living prisoners of war are much more valuable if we choose to use them as leverage.'' <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Griffiths </PERSON> both say that since retired Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s emissary, held high-level talks with the Vietnamese in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> in August 1987, there has been increased cooperation. That is evident in the field, where <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has allowed more American searchers to come in, including forensic anthropologists. But still there is a long way to go. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have turned over the remains of fewer than 300 Americans. No remains have been returned from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, where 83 Americans are listed as missing. Like <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, whose government is under the control of the Vietnamese. Can says the Vietnamese have been trying to settle the issue as fast as they can. But <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s speed depends on the cooperation the <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> mission pledged in helping the country obtain humanitarian aid from non-government organizations for disabled veterans and children. `` On their part,'' Can says, `` they will have to help us in solving the humanitarian concerns of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' By law, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is forbidden to give <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> any financial or material assistance. But it does contribute indirectly by keeping non-government charitable organizations informed of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s needs and by making it easier for the organizations to satisfy complicated regulations in sending goods and people to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. For the families of the missing, the vigil is never ending. Some of their children are now older than their fathers were when they were lost. One family, <PERSON> Rosella </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, have stayed close to their home in <LOCATION> Abington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, for nearly 20 years except to attend meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Families </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and to speak in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to keep alive the MIA-POW issue. `` We have n't been out socially in over 18 years,'' says <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, a 66-year-old bulldozer operator. `` We never go anywhere. I'm afraid a phone call will come or a car will come in the driveway with some information.'' The Fittses' son, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beret </ORGANIZATION> sergeant, has been missing since Nov. 30, 1968. He was only 21 at the time, married and a father. Now his only son is 22, older than his father was when he was reported missing. His wife did n't remarry until a year ago In March, the call the <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> had waited for came. Military officials told Mrs. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> excavation team had uncovered an undetermined number of human remains at a site in <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> where a helicopter believed carrying her son and six other military men had crashed in November 1968. The remains have been sent to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Central Identification Laboratory. But <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rosella </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, and others like them resist the finality of death. `` I've had that feeling right from the beginning that he was alive,'' says Mrs. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>. `` I just ca n't get rid of that feeling. I had a dream of seeing him in a cave alive way back.'' <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> says he had hopes his son was alive and suspected he was being held in <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> by the communist Laotian government. `` They're not dashed,'' he says `` We play the waiting game again.'' Even if the Central Identification Laboratory confirms the remains are those of his son, <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> says, he would get a second independent opinion. `` I would hate to give up and then have him walk up the driveway.'' <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> clings to the green beret his son sent him for Father's Day in 1968, shortly before he left for <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, and to an accompanying letter on a piece of yellow lined paper `` ... When you hold that beret in your hands, you hold me because we are part of each other ... Please take care if it, Dad ... Treat it like your own son, <PERSON> Dad </PERSON>, because, believe it or not, the beret you hold in front of you is your son.'' Every morning and every evening, the Fittses hold the beret in their hands. `` The minute you pick it up, you just feel him, that he's right there,'' says Mrs. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>.
