<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun., May 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>DULAC, La.: Air Force.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` I saw Ky a few months ago in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, at a reunion of soldiers who fought in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON> said when contacted recently at his home in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> `` I always thought of Gen. <PERSON> Ky </PERSON> as a committed military man and it's obvious that the men who served with him still hold him in very high regard.'' <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON> concedes he had heard rumors of gold being shipped out of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, but says he never heard of Ky being connected with any such stories. In <PERSON> Dulac </PERSON>, Ky is the president of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seafood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The operation consists of a small packing plant which processes shrimp and tuna caught by Vietnamese fishermen. Ky, who moved to <PERSON> Dulac </PERSON> several months ago, leases the processing plant from a bank in nearby <LOCATION> Houma </LOCATION>. His earlier business venture in this country, a small liquor store-delicatessen in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, ended in bankruptcy. Ky has generally tried to keep a low profile since coming to this country. He says he has gotten some financial support from other Vietnamese here and in turn works in behalf of Vietnamese refugees. `` I have spent most of my time working with and trying to help the Vietnamese people who came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as refugees,'' he says. `` That's why I am in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. I found I like the fishing business and have an opportunity to help my people here and make a living at the same time.'' In 1984, his association with refugee groups led columnist <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> to brand Ky, whose wife and family still live in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, as a leader of Vietnamese criminal elements in this country. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ky </PERSON> had smuggled $ 8 million in gold and jewels from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. `` I was stunned,'' Ky recalls. `` There was absolutely no truth in that column. If there had been the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government would have taken some action by now, do n't you think?'' <PERSON> Ky </PERSON> says he had considered suing <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> for libel but was advised against it by <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON>, who participated in an unsuccessful libel suit against <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> several years ago. `` <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON> said he found libel suits are hard to prove and you end up spending a lot of money,'' <PERSON> Ky </PERSON> says. Ky has found contentment in <LOCATION> Dulac </LOCATION>, a fishing community 80 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. He says the south <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> climate reminds him of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, complete with French-speaking natives, mosquitoes and plenty of Vietnamese to socialize with. `` Right now I'm busy trying to make a living with this processing plant and a fishing boat I bought three years ago,'' he says. `` I'm also involved in an effort to form a fishing co-op that would benefit the shrimpers in this area. `` Since I've been here I've tried to help the Vietnamese fishermen with marketing their catches and with personal details such as housing, obtaining proper licenses and insurance and such. I feel I can be a liaison between them and the established community here.'' He also spends part of his time commuting back and forth between <PERSON> Dulac </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where his youngest daughter recently graduated from law school. `` My five children have made the adjustment very well,'' he says. `` They have become Americanized and my oldest son has married an Italian girl. But, coming to this country has been harder for my wife, who stays in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to be near her children and grandchildren.'' <PERSON> Ky </PERSON> says he enjoys associating with the Vietnamese fishermen, who now comprise 65 percent of the shrimpers in the area. `` They see me, not as a general, but as another fisherman, and as a friend,'' he said. Asked whether he still dreams of returning to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, he replies, `` Yes, sometimes, but I realize it's not possible the way things are now.'' He said his main regret was not coming to this country during the war to promote and explain <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s cause to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people. `` I have found the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to be very fair and open-minded,'' he says. `` But I had no idea how the American public opinion was turning against the war. I only knew what the generals and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador and the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> were telling me. Back then, to me, they were <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.''
