<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun., May 14</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION>: of this.'' Carved swags of foliage, dogwood blossoms, fish scale designs and roses surround the windows. Rich scrollwork tops the Ionic columns. But time, weather, the successive layers of paint and some clumsy restoration efforts along the way dealt unkindly with the Scotsmen's work. Just west of the main entrance on the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Avenue side of the residence, the keystone of an architrave, an arch-like stone window frame, cracked. Rainwater seeped in and froze. The resulting collapse caused a separation of nearly an inch between two of the windowframe blocks. The ornamental border of the window is also blackened, believed to have been caused when the British burned the White House in 1812. Most of the damage is less dramatic _ a piece missing here and there from a moulding, a crack in a ledge, a damaged rosette under a windowsill. Some broken dentils, the teeth-like blocks that project under the cornice, had been rebuilt by being encased with lead, apparently in a restoration carried out when President <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> had the West Wing built in 1901. The lead boxes held the moisture inside rather than letting it escape. `` I took off one of those boxes and the stone was just like mud, like mud,'' <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> says. All of the stones had to be replaced. All in all, the work has added up to more than they expected. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has appropriated $ 2.4 million for the job, and <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> says more money may be needed. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> is saving chunks of crumbling stone to take with him to the next appropriations hearing. The stone being used in the restoration was removed from the Capitol during an expansion project in 1960 and 1961. It was quarried from <LOCATION> Aquia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> at the same time as the White House sandstone. This is the stone that the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> keeps in its maintenance yard in <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. `` Coming from the same quarry at the same time, it's the same density and has all the same characteristics,'' says <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON>, White House liaison officer for the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's as authentic as you can get.'' However, <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> says, `` one of the problems is that the big blocks of stone have been sitting there so long, and they were n't in the greatest of shape when they were taken off anyway.'' <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> estimates that about half of the stone is not usable. `` Anybody would say this is no good,'' says <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON>, pointing to a battered block lying outside the North wall, trucked there after he marked it in the maintenance yard. `` But I go in the middle. This is a very good piece of stone inside. Very tight veined. Not porous. It will give you a very smooth face, very smooth.'' The veteran stonecutter likens the process to removing the bark from a tree to find the good wood. At the White House, he makes blue chalk marks on the wall to show sections that need to be replaced. A cardboard pattern is cut to fit, and the new piece hewn from the good stone. `` The paint has sealed the stone,'' he says. `` Stone needs to breathe, too. After they remove the paint, you will be surprised at the nice little foliage that will come out that people never knew was there.'' <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> recommends that the paint be stripped from the structure every 10 years and the stone be left exposed to the air for five or six months. On this day, the master carver had clambered under a clear plastic tarpaulin erected to protect the bare wall and was watching as <PERSON> Matteo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gennaro </PERSON>, who also worked on the project at the Capitol nearly two decades ago, labored with a carbide tool and an air hammer. `` You've got to chip away little by little, so it takes time, even with the air compressor,'' <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> says. `` If you want to do the job in an accurate way, want to do what you are supposed to do, restoration is very slow motion work.''
