 That could be a typo in the title of the debut album by the quasi-jazz duo of electric guitarist <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Traut </PERSON> and bassist <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodby </PERSON>. `` The Great Yawn'' would be more like it. The record is appealing for its sparse texture, but once the novelty of these simple instrumental arrangements wears off, there's little to sustain a listener's attention. `` The Great Lawn'' is most reminiscent of <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Metheny </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Traut </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rodby </PERSON> have both played with him. But <PERSON> Traut </PERSON> is n't nearly as inventive a guitarist; he rarely strays far from the melody. And <PERSON> Traut </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rodby </PERSON> seem to be waiting for each other to take charge. As a result, the energy level peaks at about a two on a 10-point scale. The most animated the duo gets is when <PERSON> Rodby </PERSON> occasionally slaps his bass. One wonders how much the label, <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, had to do with the artists' cautious approach to their debut. The company hails the record as spanning `` many musical categories _ Jazz, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Age </ORGANIZATION>, Pop, R & amp; B ... and Beautiful.'' With <PERSON> Traut </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rodby </PERSON> trying to please so many audiences, it's a wonder they were able to come up with any notes at all. `` The Great Lawn'' is OK as background music, but bring a book along. _ By <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
