<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Field of Dreams'' goes wide May 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Costner Turns Director and Finds His Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costner </PERSON>, clad in his customary costume of jeans, T-shirt, sweater and day-old beard, arrived late for an interview but presented a valid excuse: He had been picking up tips on film directing from movie giant <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>. `` I need all the help I can get, and who could be a better teacher?'' remarked <PERSON> Costner </PERSON>, who starts directing himself in a film next July. <PERSON> Costner </PERSON>'s modest office at <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION> studios, where he once worked as a laborer, displays evidence of the new project. On the walls are dozens of note-pad pages detailing each scene of the film, as yet untitled. Next he plans to storyboard _ an artist's concept of each camera angle. `` I need to have that backup,'' he explained. `` I'll leave a window for new things to come in -LRB- during filming -RRB-. I need to communicate to many people what I'm trying to do. Those ideas can be built upon.'' <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> gave no specifics on what he had learned from <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>, but said both men had been `` dancing around each other'' in search of a mutual project. `` The only time I worked for <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> was when I did an ` Amazing Stories' for him,'' the actor said, referring to the old TV show. Three years ago, <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> was known mostly for playing the corpse in `` The Big Chill.'' Then came `` Silverado,'' `` The Untouchables'' and `` No Way Out.'' For his new film, `` Field of Dreams,'' he reportedly was paid $ 2.5 million. So why take on the added labor of directing his next film? `` I have to maintain interest in what I'm doing. This particular subject generates a certain amount of interest for me. When this project was born, it was not on the surface a very commercial movie. Yet I believe it's very commercial. `` The theme of it is people who want to talk to each other but ca n't, because of the language barrier -LRB- between white settlers and Indians -RRB-. It's a period piece set in the 1860s. This is not a movie to set the record straight, or to reinvent what happened. It's just a theatrical piece, but it's more than that, too. There's a lot of action in it.'' There's not much action in `` Field of Dreams,'' a baseball fantasy which some critics have described as Capra-esque. <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> plays an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> farmer who heeds a mystery voice and builds a baseball diamond in his cornfield; soon the ghosts of the infamous <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> team show up to play. <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> acknowledged that the script, based on the novel `` Shoeless Joe'' by W.P. <PERSON> Kinsella </PERSON>, was a tough sell. Writer-director <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Alden </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> worked on it for six years before getting it made. `` I did n't have to be convinced of it,'' <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> remarked. `` The minute I read it, I thought that I would want to do this movie. `` Why? I do n't know. I make movies, and you need to have subjects. The amount of movies I'll do in my life are numbered; it's a finite number. As a script passes over me, it has to reach me emotionally. I do n't care what genre it is, comedy or action or something else. Those do n't dictate what I'll do. But it just has to have a certain amount of poignancy. `` ` Field of Dreams' did. It also had what I'm always looking for: other strong, strong characters. So I knew that we would be able to attract good actors.'' Among them: <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON>, <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Liotta </PERSON>. <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> was born in a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb, son of a power lineman who was part-Cherokee -LRB- which helps explain his next project -RRB-. His father's work required repeated moves, and <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> recalls of school, `` I was always on the outside.'' He studied marketing at <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fullerton </ORGANIZATION>, but also acted in a community theater. After marrying his college sweetheart, <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, a former Snow White at <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> quit a marketing job to try <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. He spent six years as a set worker at <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, studying at night in acting workshops. After his flashback scene was cut from `` The Big Chill,'' <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasdan </PERSON> cast him as the hell-raising gunslinger in `` Silverado.'' He clicked immediately. Because he believes he should support all his films, <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> did the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> media whirl for `` Field of Dreams.'' He readily admits that he does n't enjoy it. He is an extremely private man, yet he does n't dwell on his loss of privacy. `` As many doors that close to you, there are others that open up,'' he reasoned. `` I do n't think anybody has been able to resolve the privacy issue. You still see people who have a certain amount of fame and do n't know how to deal with it. `` There's no good answer for when something that is unique to an individual _ their privacy _ is taken away. ... When you experience the loss of that, it's something you'll never ever get back in your life. There's no reason to cry or to pout. `` It's something I'll never get back. It's like my daughter as she grows older, she'll never be a baby again. You have to enjoy those times. My son just started to walk. We probably will not have any more children, so there will never be another helpless, helpless child. That phase is gone.'' The Costners recently bought a getaway home in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>, but their main residence is not on the trendy <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, but in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, a few miles from the <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rose </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bowl </LOCATION>. `` We bought our first home in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` A lot of our friends are out there, so we can keep those relationships up.''
