<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Barbara Mandrell Revives Memories Of Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Entertainer <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> curtailed her career as she recovered from the physical and emotional injuries of an automobile accident. She also tried to forget the tragedy, which claimed the life of a young man. Now, though, she's revived those memories in her upcoming autobiography for <ORGANIZATION> Bantam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>, `` Never Say Never.'' `` Until this book, I have never shared these things except with my neurosurgeon and my attorney,'' the 40-year-old singer said in an interview. `` Other than this book, I have kind of reached a point where I'm tired of being asked about it I chose to forget it. But the tragedy was part of my life, and I had to put it in. In order for people to know me, I felt I must tell the down side. The chapter on the crash was very difficult to do.'' <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> was involved in a two-car collision north of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> on Sept. 11, 1984. She suffered a concussion and fractures to her leg and ankle. Her two children also were hurt, but not seriously. However, the driver of the other car, a 19-year-old college student, died. The book is being written with author <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vecsey </PERSON>, who helped country queen <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> write her `` Coal Miner's Daughter.'' Finishing the autobiography is just one of a multitude of projects for the singer who's been a recording artist for 20 years. Her second gospel album, `` Precious Memories,'' has just been released. Her Las Vegas-style show, regarded as one of the best among country music-oriented performers, is undergoing its annual fine-tuning. She has had one week-long stint performing in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> this year and has two more scheduled. `` My throat wo n't take more than a week at a time,'' she said. And she is selecting songs for another country album due out in the fall. `` I'm working a lot more this year,'' she said. `` I told my agent that except for January and July, to book me three days a month. But some of those three days turned into a week.'' She's rarely been off the TV screen since her network variety show that began in 1980 and lasted two seasons, `` <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> and the Mandrell Sisters.'' She's done a half dozen specials with comedian <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>, including his most recent one in March. And she's been in countless other TV specials, ranging from appearances with former President and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to one celebrating the Special Olympics. `` I just said no to two more recently,'' she said. One of them was to be taped during a week she and her family had set aside for camping. `` My priorities were to be a mommy and wife that week,'' she said. Her gospel album is a follow-up to her previous gospel-oriented `` He Set My Life to Music,'' which won a Grammy Award in 1983. The new one includes such gospel standards as `` Peace in the <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>,'' `` Old Rugged Cross,'' `` Just a Closer Walk With Thee'' and `` I Love to Tell the Story.'' `` It was hard to narrow it down to the 20 we picked,'' <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> said. `` I had the best time doing this album. For any <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, especially one who sings for a living, the feeling is very special. `` These are songs that I feel are mine and you feel are yours. They belong to each of us. We grew up singing them. I had so many memories as I recorded them, of singing them in church or singing along to the radio. `` This was a nice, unexpected pleasure. Now I'll have these on record for the rest of my life. When I'm gone, my children and grandchildren will have them.'' She has a persistent passion for another hit record to join her others: `` I Was Country -LRB- When Country Was n't Cool -RRB-,'' `` Married, But Not to Each Other,'' `` Only a Lonely Heart Knows,'' `` Sleeping Single in a Double Bed'' and `` If Loving You Is Wrong -LRB- I Do n't Want to Be Right -RRB-.'' `` It's a never-ending desire. My biggest goal is to stay close enough in tune with what the public wants in order to earn the career they are giving me. I've never been satisfied with me. I always want to be better and I pray I never lose that desire. `` We're chomping at the bit to make my show better. I compete with me.''
