<HEAD>Researchers Try To Develop Artificial Oyster Reefs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Marine researchers hoping to boost oyster production in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> are experimenting with reefs of coal ash and cement. Oyster fishermen used to dump the shells back into the water, providing a nice hard bed that the oysters could anchor to, but they since discovered there was a market for the shells in road-building and calcium supplements. `` If the baby oyster falls on something hard, then he attaches to it and forms a shell; if he fall on the mud bottom, then he dies,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>. The utility, which has a steady supply of ash, is working with <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and state agencies on an aggregate of ash and cement mixed and molded into baseball-sized pellets. Clusters of pellets form the reefs. Adult oysters were put into four ponds with artificial reefs several weeks ago. Results may not come for a year, the time it takes for oysters to mature. But in a study in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, `` we saw no difference in mortality in oyster growth or ash and concrete versus oyster growth on clam shells,'' said <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, associate dean of marine studies at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION>. Preliminary figures also indicate the artificial beds could be cheaper than buying clam shells, which are dredged from lakes <LOCATION> Pontchartrain </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Maurepas </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> _ a practice decried by environmentalists. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> $ 150,000 last year putting clam shells in the Gulf and $ 12,500 on oyster shells, Price said. Researchers expect the aggregate to cost $ 9 to $ 10 per ton, compared with $ 15 a ton for shells, <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON> said. `` If we ca n't beat the price of the clam shells, then we've priced ourselves out of the market.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Johns Hopkins University $20 Million Heart Disease Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAGERSTOWN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers will be looking for 5,000 older recruits for a $ 20 million, four-year study of the causes of heart disease and strokes _ blamed for more than half the deaths of people aged 65 and older. The <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Researchers </ORGANIZATION>, funded by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, will be recruiting people 65 and older in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, Md.; <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` It's only recently that we understand that getting older does n't have to be associated with these diseases,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Fried </PERSON>, who will lead the study. `` There is room to prevent these diseases and enhance the health of older adults. That is really what the goal of this study is.'' The four sites were chosen because they had a stable population of people ages 65 and over, and had enough trained medical personnel to do the tests, said Dr. <PERSON> Teri </PERSON> <PERSON> Manolio </PERSON> of the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Participants will be given a physical and asked about their eating and health habits and medical and reproductive history. Researchers will measure heartbeats, breathing, blood sugar and cholesterol, and will determine whether there is any narrowing of arteries linking the heart and brain. Participants will be contacted every six months by telephone and in person. After three years, they will be asked to have a follow-up examination. Fried said initial test results would be compiled within two years. Final research results are expected to be released in four years.
