<FIRST>r f PM-PurchasingReport     05-01 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Purchasing Report,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purchasing Managers Say April Economic Growth Rose Modestly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's economy continued to grown in April at a somewhat faster pace than in March, but at about the same rate as in the first quarter, the nation's purchasing managers said in a report for release today. The levels of production and new orders both registered increases last month after posting declines in the rate of growth in March, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purchasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. Inventory buying did not fuel the pace of the growth, as inventories declined for the fourth consecutive month, said the group, based in <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. New export orders increased at the highest rate since December, after registering three consecutive months of lower rates of growth Of the 67 percent of the members who said they export, 28 percent reported better export orders in April, up sharply from 22 percent in both February and March. The 4 percent who reported lower export orders is down sharply from the 9 percent who said so in March. `` The economy entered the second quarter on a higher note than it ended the first quarter,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bretz </PERSON>, chairman of the industry group. `` A surprising increase in new export orders appears to have fueled the brisk rebound from March's sharply lower growth. Nevertheless, most other indicators signal a moderate rate of growth in the economy in the months ahead,'' he said in a statement. The group's Purchasing Managers' Index climbed to 53 percent in April, a healthy increase from 50.4 percent in March. This was the 33rd consecutive month this leading indicator registered over 50 percent. A reading above 50 percent indicates the economy is generally expanding; below 50, the economy is generally contracting. <PERSON> Bretz </PERSON> said the index averaged 52.4 percent in the first four months of 1989. If that average continues the rest of the year, it would be consistent with real rate of growth in gross national product of about 2.5 percent, he said.
</TEXT>
