<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-CoalTax     05-01 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Coal Tax,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peabody Loses Arizona Tax Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coal company seeking more than $ 42 million in refunds on <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> state taxes it paid for mining operations on the Navajo and Hopi Indian reservations lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s transaction privilege tax properly was imposed on the <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s on-reservation mining Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Flagstaff </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, argued that the tax infringes on tribal sovereignty and is pre-empted by federal law. State courts rejected those arguments after finding that the taxes imposed no burden on the tribes. Under lease agreements, Peabody mines coal from <LOCATION> Navajo </LOCATION> tribal land at the <LOCATION> Kayenta </LOCATION> Mine and from the Navajo-Hopi joint-use tribal land at the Black Mesa Mine. Virtually all of the coal mined at the two sites is sold to electric power consortiums under contracts that reimburse Peabody for all state privilege taxes it pays. From 1970 through 1979, <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> paid the state tax without protest. But the company's lawsuit against the state and its <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> sought refunds for taxes paid from 1980 through 1985 under protest. Lawyers for the coal company said that by 1986 the amount in controversy was about $ 42 million. With interest, that sum has grown. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, 88-1399.
</TEXT>
