<HEAD>Annual Wage Growth Hits 14-Year High in Fiscal 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The average Japanese worker's monthly wage climbed 3.6 percent after adjustment for inflation in the last fiscal year, the highest real growth rate in 14 years, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The wage rose to 343,716 yen, or $ 2,565, in the fiscal year ended March 31, the ministry said. The last time real growth in wages was higher was fiscal 1974, when it was 5.9 percent. The wage figure, including twice-a-year bonuses, overtime pay and various allowances such as housing, covers about 21 million workers in firms with more than 30 employees. The official said the average number of hours worked fell 0.8 percent last year to 2,100. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> has set a target of reducing annual average working hours to 1,800 by 1992.
