<HEAD>High Court To Review Detroit Newspaper Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 6 grafs of reaction after 18th graf, Knight-Ridder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to review a challenge to the partial merger of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two daily newspapers. The justices said they will judge the validity of former Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision to allow the newspapers to form a joint operating agreement. A decision is not expected until sometime in 1990. The partial merger is being challenged by a group of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> readers and advertisers. The federal Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 law authorizes the attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an exemption from federal antitrust laws. Under the joint operating agreement, The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and The Detroit News would combine their business, advertising and production departments but maintain separate news and editorial staffs. The high court, by a 7-2 vote, cleared the way for the deal March 20 when it set aside an earlier postponement ordered by Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. Only Justices <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> voted in March to continue the postponement. But it takes the votes of four justices to grant review to a formal appeal. After the March vote, lawyers for the newspapers said they would await the outcome of the formal appeal, which was acted on today. A federal appeals court panel here voted 2-1 last January to uphold <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision to allow the partial merger. The full appeals court split 5-4 last February in refusing to review the three-judge panel's ruling. Opponents to the joint operating agreement, calling themselves <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, contend that the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is not a failing newspaper even though it lost $ 10 million a year between 1981 and 1986. The opponents say the Free Press and News, which lost $ 50 million in the same period, were unprofitable solely because both papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out of business. `` The losses the papers have suffered are the product of vigorous competition,'' said the appeal acted on today. It contended that the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> deal `` threatens the independence of papers in the 25 cities that have competing dailies, since it provides a roadmap for profitable papers to obtain a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>, and the monopoly profits that can be obtained in a non-competitive market.'' But in urging the justices to reject the challenge, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration lawyers cited the `` variety of considerations'' that went into <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision. `` A newspaper in another city could hardly use this case as a guide for obtaining the attorney general's approval for a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>,'' the government lawyers said. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the News, is the nation's largest newspaper publishing group. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> is the second largest. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has said it might close the Free Press if the joint operating agreement is not consummated. `` This process has been an extraordinary lesson in patience,'' Free Press Publisher <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said after the court acted today. `` The people of the Free Press have already waited more than three years to assure this newspaper's future. `` I remain confident that what is at stake is vital to the people of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, and confident that what is proposed is fully justified.'' News Publisher <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Giles </PERSON> referred calls for comment to <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> declined comment. `` We're delighted,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>, attorney for Public Citizen, an advocacy group that handled the legal work on the challenge to the business agreement. Public Citizen had not only argued the agreement would threaten newspaper competition in other cities but that a lower court's ruling had set precedents for administrative law that would greatly restrict judicial review of executive actions `` I suspect that the fact that this case presented both issues made it doubly appealing to the court,'' <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON> said. Under the 100-year agreement, the News would receive 55 percent of the merged company's profits during the first year but that percentage would drop to 50 percent by the seventh year. Thereafter, the profits would be evenly divided. The case is <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens For an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, 88-1640.
