 <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> & amp; <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Homemade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has reached a definitive agreement with <PERSON> Dreyer </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to have some of its ice cream made at <PERSON> Dreyer </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> plant, the companies announced Monday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, general manager for <ORGANIZATION> Ben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>'s, said the company has exhausted its capacity and that demand for the ice cream is far outstripping supply. He said the company is not interested in building a third plant in the state right now. Under a three-year agreement, <PERSON> Dreyer </PERSON>'s will manufacture <ORGANIZATION> Ben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>'s products at Dreyers' <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, plant using <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> dairy products. <PERSON> Dreyer </PERSON>'s, an Oakland-Calif. - based company, makes and distributes ice cream and other dairy-based products, including <ORGANIZATION> Ben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and By 1992, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said, about 3.5 million gallons of ice cream will be produced in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>; the Waterbury-based company currently sells 5 million gallons annually, and projects it will be selling 8 million gallons a year by 1992. The company currently operates two <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> plants, one in <LOCATION> Waterbury </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>. The <LOC