<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-SexBias 1stLd-Writethru f0062 05-01 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Sex Bias, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0062,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Looks At Sex Bias Case And Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after 15th pvs, She later, to make a Scotus
roundup; edits 16th graf pvs to conform, picks up 17th, She had</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sharply divided <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today the burden is on employers to disprove sexual stereotyping when they are accused of discriminating against women. By a 6-3 vote, the justices ordered further lower court hearings in a suit against the accounting firm Price Waterhouse by <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, who said she was denied a partnership because of `` macho'' attitudes that she did not behave sufficiently ladylike. Today's ruling also is a partial victory for Price Waterhouse. The court overturned a lower court ruling that would have placed an even heavier burden of proof on the company. Moreover, only four of the justices agreed on the standards that should govern lawsuits alleging sexual stereoptyping. The absence of a court majority enunciating clear guidelines is likely to sow confusion among lower courts when deciding such cases. Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, in the court's main opinion, said when someone `` proves that her gender played a motivating part in an employment decision, the defendant may avoid a finding of liability only by proving by a preponderance of the evidence that it would have made the same decision even if it had not taken the plantiff's gender into account.'' Joining his opinion were Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, in a separate concurring opinion, agreed that in the case of Price Waterhouse, `` the burden of persuasion should shift to the employer to demonstrate by a preponderance of the evidence that it would have reached the same decision concerning <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>' candidacy absent consideration of her gender.'' But <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said she does not favor `` the strong medicine'' of forcing employers to bear the burden of proof in all such cases. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> also concurred in today's result. But in a separate opinion he said he would not require an employer to submit `` objective evidence'' to disprove sexual bias in such cases. As long as `` the employer credibly testifies that the action would have been taken for legitimate reasons alone, this should be ample proof,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. The three dissenters are Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and <PERSON> Justices </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. They voted to kill Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>' suit. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, in his opinion for the three, said there was ample evidence that Price Waterhouse did not discriminate against her intentionally. Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> quit Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's so-called `` Big Eight'' accounting firms, after she was denied promotion to partnership in 1983 _ a move that would have made her a part owner. She later became a consultant to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. In other actions today, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>: _ Agreed to review a challenge to review to the partial merger of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two daily newspapers The justices said they will judge the validity of former Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision to allow the newspapers to form a joint operating agreement. _ Agreed to hear a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration apeal aimed at allowing the government to collect potentially hundreds of millions of dollars in taxes from multinational corporations _ Refused to hear an appeal by <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> officials seeking to recover from asbestos manufacturers the cost of removing the product from public schools in the state In the sex bias case, Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> had joined Price Waterhouse in 1978 and was nominated for parntership in 1982, the only woman among 88 candidates for partnership that year. She had been very successful in getting business for the company, winning government contracts worth between $ 34 million and $ 44 million. Both her critics and supporters at Price <PERSON> Watershouse </PERSON> said she sometimes was overly agreessive, too harsh, impatient with her staff and very demanding. One critic suggested she needed to take a `` course at charm school.'' A partner who supported her for promotion told her she would stand a better chance of getting ahead if she would `` walk more femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear make-up, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.'' Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> sued Price Waterhouse on grounds it violated Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibiting on-the-job discrimination. She said sexual stereotyping, unconscious or otherwise, cost her a partnership. Professinal partnerships are covered by the 1964 law under a 1984 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here ruled in 1987 that while there appeared to be mixed motives in denying Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> a partnership, Price Waterhouse was unable to prove that `` impermissible bias was not the determinative factor'' for the decision. The appeals court said an employer must show by `` clear and convincing evidence'' they did not practice bias. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today did not go that far. The `` clear and convincing'' standard usually means that to successfully defend against a lawsuit, a company must show that the overwhelming evidence is in its favor. By contrast, the `` preponderance'' standard adopted today means Price Waterhouse can win if it can show more than half the evidence is in its favor. The case is Price Waterhouse vs. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, 87-1167.
</TEXT>
