<HEAD>Supreme Court Refuses To Hear Kodak Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 18 grafs to UPDATE with Supreme Court action; ADD
background on Texaco-Pennzoil case; picks up 14th graf pvs, ``We're not
....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to hear <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal of a federal court ruling that the company infringed on instant film and camera patents held by <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> argued that the 1985 ruling should be thrown out because <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Rya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>, who presided over the trial, had a conflict of interest in the case A federal appeals court that earlier heard <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal noted that <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> announced to both companies in 1981 that her mother-in-law owned <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> shares and that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> raised no objection. The appeals court said that it was not until 1988, well after <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>'s liability ruling against <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>, that the company objected. Since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refuses to hear the case, the federal appeal's court ruling against <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> is the final word. In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, opening arguments began today in the trial to determine the damages <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> must pay <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>. By copying <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s technology, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> forced its rival to sell some cameras below cost and enormously damaged the instant photography market, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said. The trial before Judge <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> is expected by many securities analysts to result in <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> paying Polaroid about $ 1 billion, which would be the largest patent damage award in history. The trial is expected to take four to six months. `` You start talking and I'll start listening, and as the famous saying goes, I hope you finish before I do,'' <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> lawyers. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> argued that <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> was entitled to $ 3.9 billion in lost profits because of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s sales of instant cameras and film between 1976 and 1986. In addition, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> argued that <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> is entitled to interest and triple punitive damages, bringing the total to just under $ 12 billion. In a previous trial, a judge ruled in October 1985 that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had violated seven of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s key patents on instant film and cameras _ and booted <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> out of the instant photography business, saddling it with $ 600 million of losses and an estimated $ 200 million worth of useless manufacturing equipment. The only issue in the current trial is the value of the damage caused by <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> argues that the most Polaroid should get is $ 177 million, representing a 5 percent royalty on all the instant film and cameras that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> sold from 1976 to 1986. Lawyers said the record award in a patent infringement lawsuit was approximately $ 200 million that <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> received from <ORGANIZATION> Dresser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. A multibillion-dollar verdict could force <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> to make layoffs, take on huge debt and sell subsidiaries to raise cash. It could leave the company unable to make the investments it needs to compete with Japanese film makers. If the award is near the top of the possible range, it could even force <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> into a Chapter 11 bankruptcy, just as <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was forced to reorganize when a jury ordered it to pay $ 10.3 billion to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> four years ago. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> emerged from Chapter 11 a year ago after paying <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> $ 3 billion in cash to settle the case. But securities analysts say a Chapter 11 filing is unlikely. Most Wall Street brokerage houses are predicting an award of about $ 1 billion, and traders say the stock prices of both companies already reflect that expectation. `` We're not going to see another <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> here,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Enderlin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Polaroid, which recently spent $ 1.1 billion to buy back stock and fend off a hostile takeover by <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is expected to use part of any award to lower its corporate debt <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he reckoned <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price probably will rise or fall about $ 1 for every $ 100 million of the award that is above or below Wall Street's expectations.
