<HEAD>Louisiana Governor Says Some Hospitals, Universities Likely Will
Be Closed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with governor's comments this morning.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Roemer's plan...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto BT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters' rejection of Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s tax plan will mean the likely closures of hospitals and universities and the layoffs of thousands of state employees, the governor said today `` We do n't have all the specifics yet. We'll let you know as soon as we can,'' an obviously weary <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> told reporters at an impromptu news conference. The governor was closeted late into the night Sunday with advisers to decide how to approach a budget that is now $ 700 million short of balance for the new fiscal year beginning July 1. Voters on Saturday rejected the plan by 55 percent to 45 percent, according to unofficial returns. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who traveled around the state for six weeks trying to to sell the plan, faces questions about his political future just 13 months after he took office as a reformer promising a `` new <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>.'' `` I'm not worried about that. I'm concerned about this state,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said, fielding questions on the Capitol steps. `` There will be a referendum on <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> in 2 -LCB- years.'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s plan would have shifted the tax burden away from big business, putting more of a load on individuals through the income tax. It would have reduced sales taxes and given businesses incentives to move to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and expand. The plan also included a $ 1.4 billion program to improve highways, airports and shipping ports, funded by a gasoline tax increase of 4 cents a gallon. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> touted his plan as a way to bring jobs to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, which has the nation's highest unemployment rate at 9.6 percent, and to end the state's dependence on the oil industry. The oil, gas and chemical industry paid more than half of the state taxes for nearly 50 years until its collapse in 1982. Since then, state government has hovered near bankruptcy. `` I never worked harder in my life to try to turn this around,'' the Democratic governor said. `` We're going to keep building, but not as fast as I wanted to.'' `` This plan will tell <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that we've changed, that we're ready to pay our way,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said repeatedly during his trips around the state Opponents condemned it as nothing more than a huge tax increase and said <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> had not reduced spending as promised during his 1987 campaign, when he unseated <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, an outspoken critic of the plan, said its defeat was `` going to make a real change in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>.'' He called on <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> to work with legislators in tightening spending and making major changes in its welfare programs. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> leader elected as a Republican to a suburban <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> seat on an anti-tax plank in February, compared the referendum's outcome to his own victory. `` Every day that passes, I'm more and more in awe of the intelligence and the good sense in our state,'' he said. Even with passage of the plan, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> would have been forced to cut spending by $ 200 million to keep the budget balanced. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> met all day Sunday with his closest advisers on how to cut the budget. `` The people want closures. I really believe that,'' Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Adley </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said as he left the meeting at the governor's mansion. `` They sent us a signal that we have n't done enough. `` It could be from one to several universities or more. Hospitals could be from three to five,'' the Democrat said. `` Right now we're trying to find every way in the world that a degree of services can be rendered.'' <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> has 18 public universities and eight charity hospitals. `` The people sent a signal that they want more cuts,'' added <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s chief of staff. `` I'm not sure what goes through the minds of citizens when they think of budget cuts. They think of waste, of extras. Unfortunately, to live within the limitations set here, we'll probably have to do more than the average citizen expects.'' <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON> said thousands of the state's 80,000 employees likely would lose their jobs. The administration would determine within a week all specific cuts, he said. `` When you close institutions, that means people lose jobs,'' he said. As for <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s political future, political consultant and pollster <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Renwick </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said the governor was `` badly wounded, but not critically wounded.'' <PERSON> Silas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> political scientist, said, `` <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> could n't sell his plan to blue-collar whites, many of whom think <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> is on the ball, and he could n't sell it to blacks, who did n't think there would really be thousands of jobs for them.''
