<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Detroit JOA,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees to Hear Newspaper Merger Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision Monday to review the partial merger of two <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newspapers will force <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to determine how much longer it can absorb losses from its <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, analysts said. By agreeing to hear arguments on the proposed joint operating agreement -LRB- JOA -RRB-, the court set the stage for its first review of the 19-year-old Newspaper Preservation Act. A decision is not expected until next year. The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> agreed in 1986 to merge the newspapers' production, circulation and business operations and to split profits and losses equally for most of the 100-year arrangement <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive officer, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Battn </PERSON>, said the organization would plan over the coming days what to do next. <PERSON> Batten </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> continues `` to believe strongly in the fairness and justice of our case on behalf of a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>, through spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, said it was `` reviewing the decision'' and would have no further comment. Both newspapers have been losing money for years, and <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has said it will close the smaller <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> unless the partial merger goes through. `` <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s decision would be based upon its reading of the length of time and the likelihood ... of this thing happening,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON>, communications industry analyst with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> brokerage house <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Clearly, from their point of view, they would like to eliminate the cash drain of the Free Press. ... On the other hand, if they wait it out, then they'll have half interest in a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>, which will earn considerably more for them than the loss last year. So it is a tough decision,'' <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON> said. The Free Press lost $ 18.5 million in 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> said in court filings earlier this year. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> has released no annual loss figures for the News, but <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> in testimony has estimated the News' losses at $ 75 million from 1979 through 1987. The newspapers have said closing the Free Press would cost 2,200 jobs while a joint operating agreement would mean a total of 600 to 800 jobs lost at the two papers. Free Press employees at a staff meeting took news of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision with a calm patience. `` We've been punched around so many times. It's like, okay, we'll waltz with it again,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, a feature writer. The partial merger, designed to retain newspaper competition through an exemption to federal antitrust laws, was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> last year but was tied up by court challenges from an organization of newspaper readers and advertisers, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, and the Washington-based advocacy group <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>. They argued that the newspapers' losses resulted from management decisions rather than being inherent in the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> media market and that if the deal were approved, any well-off newspaper publishing group could deliberately create conditions for an antitrust exemption. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration attorneys countered that a `` variety of considerations'' had been behind the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. `` A newspaper in another city could hardly use this case as a guide for obtaining the attorney general's approval for a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>,'' the government lawyers said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, a lawyer for Public Citizen, predicted far-reaching results from the court's decision to hear arguments. `` It is the first test the court has heard under the Newspaper Preservation Act. It is likely it will decide the meaning of the act and the scope of the act for the future,'' <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said. A federal appeals court panel in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> voted 2-1 in January to uphold the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to allow the partial merger. The full appeals court then split 5-4 in February in refusing to review the three-judge panel's ruling. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 7-2 vote, cleared the way for the deal March 20 when it set aside an earlier postponement ordered by Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. Only Justices <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> voted in March to continue the postponement; the votes of four justices are needed to grant review to a formal appeal. When the court's stay was lifted, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> proposed proceeding with the partial merger. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> declined to do so. No stay is in effect, and the newspapers would have the option of merging while awaiting the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision on the case. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, is the nation's largest newspaper publishing group. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, is the second largest.
