<HEAD>Treasury Bill Rates Fall In Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities fell in Monday's auction. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.64 percent, down from 8.66 percent last week. Another $ 7 billion was sold in six-month bills at a discount rate which also averaged 8.64 percent, down from 8.72 percent last week. The rates were the lowest since April 17 when three-month bills sold for 8.57 percent and six-month bills averaged 8.59 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 8.96 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,781.60 and 9.16 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,563.20. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, dipped to 9.22 percent last week from 9.28 percent the previous week.
