<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens As Intervention Has Little Impact</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Most European financial markets were closed Monday for a holiday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar wound up higher against all major currencies in a thin market Monday as an unexpectedly strong economic assessment from the nation's purchasing managers triggered buying. Gold prices barely budged. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 377.45 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EDT, 5 cents lower than Friday's late bid. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Polce </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said intervention by a few central banks had little lasting effect on the dollar's movement. Trading volume was light in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Most major European financial markets were closed for a holiday. Individual transactions have more of an impact on exchange rates in a market in which relatively fewer trades are taking place. Foreign exchange dealers attributed part of the dollar's strength to a monthly survey by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purchasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, which suggested economic growth regained momentum in April The purchasing managers' index, which measures new orders, production, vendor deliveries, inventory and employment, went up to 53 percent in April after falling to 50.4 percent in March. Last month's growth rate was roughly the same as the first quarter's pace An implication of the purchasing managers' survey was that economic activity may not be slowing enough to induce the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to ease its grip on credit. This would mean interest rates would remain at current levels. Rising interest rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year have enhanced the appeal of dollar-denominated investments. Here are late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Friday's late rates: 134.125 Japanse yen, up from 133.05; 1.89065 West German marks, up from 1.8810; 1.6870 Swiss francs, up from 1.6755; 6.375 French francs, up from 6.3580; 1,383.25 Italian lire, up from 1,377.00; and 1.18725 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1853 The dollar strengthened against the British pound in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading. Sterling was quoted at $ 1.6798, less expensive for buyers than Friday's late rate of $ 1.6855. Gold prices were little changed in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dealings. There were no quotes available from overseas. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery edged up to $ 378.20 a troy ounce from Friday's settlement of $ 377.90. Silver bullion for current delivery settled at $ 5.646 a troy ounce on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex compared to $ 5.601 on Friday.
