<BYLINE>Gloomy Weather Forecasts Force Grains Higher ^By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices rose strongly Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to long-range forecasts of below-average rainfall in several grain-producing states. On other markets, gasoline and crude oil prices rallied; cattle and hogs were up, and gold and silver prices gained moderately. Wheat settled 4 cents to 6 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.23 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 4 \ cents to 5 -RCB- cents higher with May at $ 2.74 a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 6 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 1.84 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 12 -RCB- cents to 17 -RCB- cents higher with May at $ 7.35 \ The increased grain and soybean prices came on the heels of the 30 - and 90-day forecasts released Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which predicted a return to dry conditions in the western half of the Farm Belt, including <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> The forecasts fueled talk of a return of drought conditions, pushing up prices across the board. `` It was a very typical weather-related price movement,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` There is a lot of uncertainty in the market, and the market should reflect that uncertainty into the summer.'' Wheat finished strong despite doubt over the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's position on continuing subsidized grain sales to foreign countries. <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> noted that a lot of people are questioning the export subsidy program, which finances cheap wheat sales to certain