le and hogs will be brought to market, while others are buying because they expect a decrease in deliveries. Live cattle settled .02 cent to .37 cent higher, with June at 71.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .10 cent higher with May at 76.30 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent lower to .30 cent higher with June at 46.92 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .13 cent to 2 cents lower with May at 30.87 cents a pound. Gold and silver futures settled slightly higher on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as traders cashed in on what is thought to be an oversold market Despite the rise in prices, the market remains bearish because of the lowering of the inflation mentality, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Without the threat of inflation there is little reason for investors to buy gold. Gold settled 20 cents to 80 cents higher with May at $ 378.20 a troy ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 6 cents higher with May at $ 5.646 a troy ounce.
