<HEAD>Say Consumer Faith in Economy Remains Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer confidence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy remains strong despite growing indications of a slowdown caused by rising interest rates, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> group </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. Its monthly Consumer Confidence Index, which tracks the spending plans and perceptions about the economy in 5,000 households nationwide, totaled 116.3 points in April, down only slightly from the 117.7 figure in March. The index is calculated on a 1985 base year of 100 points. An analysis of the latest index showed 28.8 percent of respondents believe current business conditions are good, unchanged from a month earlier, and 34.7 percent believe jobs are plentiful, slightly higher than the March percentage. Respondents were slightly less optimistic about the next six months, however. Only 16.5 percent anticipate an improvement in business conditions, vs. 18 percent who said so a month earlier. The index also showed only 3.1 percent of respondents plan to purchase a home, unchanged from March, reflecting continued concern with rising interest rates and the resulting higher cost of financing a mortgage. Nonetheless, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in its analysis, the index showed consumer confidence remained resiliently high. `` The consumer's sustained sense of well-being is justified, at least for the moment, by the continuing vigor of the economy,'' said <PERSON> Fabian </PERSON> <PERSON> Linden </PERSON>, executive director of the group's consumer research center. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, describes itself as a worldwide business network of companies and executives in more than 50 nations that conducts research and provides forums for exchanging information.
