<HEAD>Tough New Provision's Effective Date Delayed Until Oct. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with Levin reax. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on Monday delayed until Oct. 1 the effective date of a tough new tax provision aimed at ensuring that employers' health insurance plans do not discriminate in favor of higher-paid workers. `` The cost of compliance with Section 89 -LRB- of the Internal Revenue Code -RRB- as it presently stands is excessive,'' Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> meeting. `` The law needs to be changed and we stand ready to encourage, support and work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to revise and improve it.'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s announcement of the three-month delay in the deadline for employers to comply with the law was greeted by loud applause from the business audience. Business has made repeal or modification of the Section 89 law as major goal this year. The law, proposed by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, was enacted as part of the 1986 tax overhaul. It requires employers to conduct a lengthy series of complex tests to demonstrate that their tax-deductible employee benefits, especially health insurance, are not weighted against workers making less than $ 50,000 a year. Paperwork required by the law is so voluminous that some employers are threatening to withdraw health insurance coverage for all employees. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s announcement came on the eve of a public hearing on the disputed section by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>, the committee chairman, and most members of the committee have signed a bill to significantly relax the testing requirements on employers. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, also has called for overhaul of the provision. `` We have ... asked the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to work with the administration to find ways to revise Section 89 to make its requirements less burdensome on business,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. The regulations issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` impose unreasonable compliance burdens on business,'' he added. The Section 89 rules went into effect on Jan. 1 but the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> waived compliance requirements until July 1 and agreed that no employer would be penalized if a good-faith effort to follow the rules were made the remainder of 1989. Under <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s bill, employers that provide a health plan would have to offer coverage costing workers $ 10 a week or less -LRB- $ 25 or less for a family plan -RRB- to 90 percent of employees. Higher-paid workers would be taxed on the value of coverage that was better than provided other employees. Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., said the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s decision was `` only a first step in cleaning up the administrative nightmare associated'' with the tax `` This should give employers the assurance that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> wo n't rush into enforcing this flawed provision, and it should give the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> time to consider options ranging from substantial simplification to outright repeal,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said
