<HEAD>Labor Department Proposes $1.15 Million In Fines For Fatal Tunnel
Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with reaction from second company;
picks up 6th graf, `Connors said ...'. A version moved on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> proposed $ 1.15 million in fines for two contractors cited Monday for 115 safety violations in a methane gas explosion last year that killed three sewer tunnel workers. <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Healy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> McCook </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, was cited for 68 willful violations carrying fines of $ 680,000; <ORGANIZATION> CH2M </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Corvallis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, was cited for 47 willful violations carrying penalties of $ 470,000. <PERSON> Healy </PERSON>, the main contractor for the project, and CH2M, hired to supervise construction on the tunnel, have 15 days to appeal the citations and penalties to the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Connors </PERSON>, regional administrator of <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Malina </PERSON> said in a statement that his company had cooperated with <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation and the citations were `` not a verdict but rather a starting point.'' `` We intend to vigorously defend against the <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> citations and look forward to presenting all the facts,'' he said. CH2M said in a statement the company was `` surprised and distressed'' by the citations and that all equipment listed in the 47 citations belonged to the contractor. `` The responsibilities of CH2M <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> as program manager do not include supervising or performing any of the construction'' on the project, the statement said. <PERSON> Connors </PERSON> said his agency's investigation found that electrical power had not been turned off after workers were evacuated from the tunnel Nov. 10 after dangerously high levels of methane were detected. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Sturgeon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohne </PERSON>, 49, of Big <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sochacki </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>; were killed by a explosion after they re-entered the tunnel to check methane levels. Work has not resumed at the tunnel, but spokesmen for the project have said they hope work might resume later this month.
