<HEAD>Japanese Company Buys Celebrity Site For More Than $100 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Hotel Bel-Air, haunt of movie stars and the Hollywood elite, was sold Monday to a Japanese company for more than $ 100 million by its <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> owner. The price for the rambling, low-rise landmark works out to more than $ 1 million per room, a record for hotel sales that real estate experts say is unlikely to be surpassed any time soon. It demonstrates Japanese investors' continued appetite for such `` trophy'' real estate as prestigious big-city office buildings and resort property. <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> oil heiress <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, through her <ORGANIZATION> Rosewood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, announced that the <LOCATION> Bel-Air </LOCATION> had been sold to <PERSON> Sekitei </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaihatsu </PERSON>, a 95-year-old <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> company that operates hotels, resorts and restaurants in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rosewood </PERSON> said the landmark, which had been on the market for about two months, sold for more than $ 100 million, but did n't reveal the precise amount <PERSON> Rosewood </PERSON> will continue to operate the hotel, it said. The <LOCATION> Bel-Air </LOCATION>'s restaurant ranks with the nearby <LOCATION> Polo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lounge </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> among the city's chic dining spots. Recent diners have ranged from entertainers <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> executive <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisner </PERSON>. One-time hotel resident <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> once called the hotel the best wife he'd ever had. The Hotel Bel-Air, which sits on <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' tony west side not far from the <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> campus, has room rates ranging from $ 195 to $ 1,300 per night, with an average of $ 375 a night. Occupancy averages 90 percent, compared with a national average of 68 percent. Ms. <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>'s company bought the mission-style hotel and its 11-acre grounds in 1982 for $ 22.7 million and spent $ 20 million renovating it and adding 30 rooms, for a total of 92 rooms. The previous record per-room price for a hotel was $ 200 million, or more than $ 750,000 a room, paid for the <ORGANIZATION> Beverly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> by the Sultan of <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> in 1987. Last week, another Japanese company completed purchase of the nearby <LOCATION> Riviera </LOCATION> golf and tennis club for more than $ 100 million.
