<HEAD>Labor Department Sues Shearson For Alleged Misuse Of Teamsters Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Monday sued a brokerage firm, an investment manager and several trustees of $ 561 million in Teamsters union benefit funds for allegedly abusing their positions for financial gain through stock deals and other transactions. Among the allegations in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> suit is that the <LOCATION> Utica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, office of the brokerage firm <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> manipulated stock purchases for the funds to benefit other clients. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, investment manager <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Farnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and several of their agents were charged with violating federal pension laws by causing the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> funds to engage in prohibited financial transactions. A copy of the complaint was released by <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after normal business hours Monday and attempts to reach <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> officials were unsuccessful. A telephone call to <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Utica </LOCATION> office was not answered and a woman who answered the phone at <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said there was no one available to comment. Included in the alleged abuses were `` stock parking'' schemes in which <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, acting through three of its employees, set up an account in its <LOCATION> Utica </LOCATION> office that it used to purchase stocks with the funds' assets. Instead of immediately transferring the stocks to the funds, the suit alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> `` parked'' them for a period of time to determine their short-term profitability and used accounting tricks to transfer securities that had increased in value to the accounts of friends, relatives and customers of two former <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> brokers who handled the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> account. One of the former brokers, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Inserra </PERSON>, allegedly used his knowledge of the funds' investment plans to benefit some of his individual clients by purchasing stock for them just before the funds made large purchases of the same stock. <PERSON> Inserra </PERSON> then allegedly sold the individual clients' stock at the higher prices caused by the bulk purchase. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> also allegedly benefited through fee arrangements with banks issuing certificates of deposits to the union funds. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> allegedly concealed indirect fees on assets invested in the certificates; <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> allegedly was paid to manage those investments but performed no services. The funds involved are the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> and Retirement Fund, the <ORGANIZATION> Upstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and Hospital Fund. Together they have about 65,000 participants and had $ 561,231,396 in cumulative assets as of the end of 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. Eight current and former trustees of the funds were named as defendants for allegedly violating their fiduciary responsibily to the plans. The suit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, seeks a court order requiring the defendants to determine and restore with interest all losses incurred by the funds because of improper activities. It also seeks court-appointed monitors to review the practices of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> and an order prohibiting four current and former employees of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> from involvement in pension plans covered by the federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act.
