<HEAD>Wholesale Gasoline Rallies Anew</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs on BP raising its Alaskan crude price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The energy futures market turned mixed in light trading Monday, with gasoline and crude oil rising in price and home heating oil continuing to decline. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the June contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline settled 1.39 cents higher at 72.61 cents a gallon. The May contract, which expired on Friday, had lost 3.91 cents. The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 24 cents to $ 20.66 a 42-gallon barrel, after falling 50 cents on Friday. June heating oil, which gained 0.34 cent Friday, closed 0.31 cent lower at 49.46 cents a gallon. Heating oil has been on the decline in reaction to the warmer weather. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, an energy analyst at <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, attributed the rise in gasoline to strong fundamentals, which, in turn, helped push up crude prices. `` We're motoring into the driving season and ... approaching the Memorial Day holiday,'' he said. Gasoline has been the market's star performer recently due to concerns of tight supplies for the summer driving season. Those concerns escalated following the Exxon oil spill off the Alaskan coast in March and a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> explosion recently. In a related move Monday, BP Exploration raised the price of North Slope Alaskan crude by more than $ 2 a barrel, pushing the it to its highest level in more than three years. The increase is partly attributable to the Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> oil spill and interruptions of production in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodgsdon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s chief petroleum economist. <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION> set its May contract price at $ 19.77 on the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> and $ 19.33 on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. The difference reflects a variation in transportation costs. The prices represented a $ 2.25 a barrel increase on the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> and $ 2.20 more on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. BP is the only North Slope producer that makes its prices public, but other North Slope producers usually follow <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION>'s lead.
