<FIRST>r f AM-BankingConference     05-01 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banking Conference,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Official: Repeal of Interstate Banking Ban Would Even Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Repealing the barriers to interstate banking would remove handicaps on the industry in the national and international marketplace, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. A repeal of such barriers `` could do much to level the global playing field and to restore American banks to prominence around the world,'' <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> at its annual conference. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> also said repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act, which bars banks from engaging in securities activities, would benefit investors and borrowers and give customers better access to the securities markets. He said American banks are retrenching in the world market, while those in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> keep enlarging their share. American banks' international lending is down almost 15 percent, to about $ 100 billion, from its 1983 peak of $ 121 billion, while Japanese lending has gone from $ 28 billion to $ 129 billion, German and Swiss lending has more than doubled and British lending has expanded by nearly 50 percent, he said. In addition, <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said, Japanese dominance has extended to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, to no small extent `` because no bank is permitted to have a nationwide presence in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' He said it might be argued more accurately that <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> banks are competing against Japanese and German banks. `` At year-end 1987, 111 Japanese banks held over 40 percent of the deposits in the 500 largest banks in the world. Ninety <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks were in the top 500, but they accounted for only 11 percent of total deposits. `` No <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank is among the largest 25 banks in the world, and Japanese banks occupy the top 10 positions,'' he said. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said removing the barriers to interstate banking also would `` result in more diversified and safer instutitions _ a highly desirable result in these difficult times.'' He said that while the presence of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks abroad has decreased, the reverse is true in this country, where 259 foreign banks operate through subsidiaries, branches and agencies, with combined assets of more than $ 600 billion, about 20 percent of total <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> banking assets. He said international banking has increased twice as fast as world trade over the past 25 years and four times as fast as world gross national product. He said a new agreement on risk-based capital signed by a dozen major industrial nations, known as the <LOCATION> Basle </LOCATION> Accord, should help redress inequities among banks incorporated in different nations by establishing uniform capital standards for banks that are internationally active. As for the banking and securities issue, <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will review the situation within a year `` with an eye toward allowing bank holding companies to engage in underwriting and trading equity securities.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> recently granted limited securities powers to bank holding companies. He said fulfillment of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s move toward a unified banking market and a uniform regulatory environment `` could mean the creation of the largest unified banking market in the world.'' However, a top <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> official told the group separately Monday they need not fear a `` fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' or reciprocity that would shut them out when the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s trade barriers fall in 1992 Sir <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittan </PERSON>, vice president of the commission, said the commission's objective is a liberalized, competitive market as open as possible to the world. As long as European Community institutions are not discriminated against and genuinely have access to American markets, bankers in this country have nothing to fear, he said. But a West German banking official said the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> should consider imposing reciprocity sanctions on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to put pressure on that country to open its banking markets and to liberalize trade, much as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> banks have done with some success. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohlhaussen </PERSON>, a director of <ORGANIZATION> Commerzbank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, said reciprocity is of `` absolutely no problem'' to American institutions in his country because of good banking relations. `` Our relations with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, however, have not always been of this character,'' he said. <PERSON> Kohlhaussen </PERSON> said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has used the reciprocity argument against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to press <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for access to its market. He said that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> often bring up the image of `` Fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, probably to divert attention from ` Fortress <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.''' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> have been assuaged of their fears about a `` European fortress.'' But he added that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> represented `` a fortress where the doors were open, but when you came in, there were a whole lot of compartments, a whole lot of rooms that were locked up, one against the other.''
